<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Official Admits Terrorism Law Blunder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- British Home Secretary Jack Straw
admitted Wednesday that sections of Britain's Prevention of
Terrorism Act have not been in force for more than a year due to a
drafting blunder.
</P>
<P>
He told the parliament that technical flaws in the drafting of
orders continuing the act last year meant that certain parts of
the act effectively had been dropped and had not been in force
since March 1998.
</P>
<P>
"I therefore come before the House (of Commons) today to
apologize for this regrettable error, for which I take full
responsibility," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The blunder means it is not currently an offense to hold
articles relate to terrorist activity and to collect information
for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
New laws would be introduced to make these offense again as
quickly as possible, the Home Secretary said, adding that there
was plenty of other legislation on the statute book under which
terrorists could be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
Straw said no-one had been arrested since March 1998 under the
faulty provisions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
