<HEADLINE> 3 Lebanese Civilians Wounded in S. Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Three Lebanese civilians were
wounded Wednesday in Israeli attacks on villages in south
Lebanon, the Voice of the People radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Abdelhadi Fahs, 70, and Ali Zahweh, 12, were wounded when
their house in the village of Kabrikha on the north of the
Israeli occupied border zone in south Lebanon, was hit by an
Israeli shell.
</P>
<P>
Badia Khiamy, 60, was wounded when Israeli warplanes fired
eight rockets at suspected Lebanese guerrillas' positions in a
valley near the Yater inside the occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli attack came as a response to previous operations
launched by guerrillas of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party
of God, on its positions inside the border enclave.
</P>
<P>
Late Tuesday night, a member of the pro-Israeli South Lebanon
Army (SLA) and a Lebanese civilian were killed in roadside bombs
by unidentified Lebanese guerrillas. An Israeli soldier was
wounded in the attacks.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting to dislodge Israeli occupation forces
and its ally SLA out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
