<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Civil Servants Can Retire at 60 with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania will pay all
benefits to civil and public servants who retire at the compulsory
age of 60 in accordance with a new law, a senior official said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Permanent Secretary of the Finance Ministry Raphael Mollel said
that the Public Service Retirement Benefits Act of 1999 also
guarantees all the benefits to servants who retire at voluntary
age of 55.
</P>
<P>
Mollel said that the new law, which is to become effective on
July 1 this year, raises the compulsory and voluntary retirement
ages from 55 to 60 and from 50 to 55 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The permanent secretary said that all relevant authorities have
been urged to submit files of compulsory or voluntary retirees to
his ministry for checking procedures for their benefits.
</P>
<P>
Mollel also disclosed that under the new system, public
servants shall be allowed to retire by using an affidavit.
</P>
<P>
"Any one who will use an affidavit and later proved otherwise
will be met with legal measures," he warned. "All the salaries
earned through presenting such an affidavit will be deducted from
the retirement benefits."
</P>
<P>
Tanzania reduced its civil service from 355,000 to 271,000 last
year, a 24 percent cut over a five-year period to make it more
effective and efficient. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
