<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Parties Still Disagree on Election Model </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Lesotho Congress
for Democracy and three other leading parties are still in
disagreement over the appropriate electoral model to be used in
elections scheduled for early next year, according to reports
reaching here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This emerged after talks in Lesotho capital Maseru Wednesday
between the ruling party and the opposition alliance -- consisting
of the Basotho National Party, the Basotholand Congress Party and
the Marematlou Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
The participants issued a joint statement after the meeting,
saying that there were differences during the talks.
</P>
<P>
It was felt this could be ironed out within the Interim
Political Authority (IPA) set up to facilitate the election.
</P>
<P>
The statement said all the parties, except the ruling party,
were in favor of a 100 percent proportional representation model.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Congress for Democracy was in favor of a dual model,
 comprising the "first past the post" method currently in use and
proportional representation. It felt any drastic change should be
referred to a national referendum.
</P>
<P>
But the other parties felt a referendum was outside the
Interim Political Authority mandate, and that it would be
expensive. The parties further felt there was a limited period
before the holding of the election.
</P>
<P>
The parties decided that the review of the structure of the
Independent Electoral Commission, as well as the issue of
security, should be further addressed by the Interim Political
Authority.
</P>
<P>
However, an understanding was reached by the parties concerning
the subject of "consensus".
</P>
<P>
They agreed on a definition to be adopted by the Interim
Political Authority that consensus was defined in terms of the IPA
Act, which meant agreement by a substantial majority after
lobbying of opinions and without a vote.
</P>
<P>
The issue of consensus had posed a serious problem for the IPA.
</P>
<P>
Political observers hailed the agreement among the political
leaders on a common understanding of the word.
</P>
<P>
They said this would pave the way for the continuation of
preparations for the election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
