<HEADLINE> IDB Finances Water and Sanitation Project in Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) on Wednesday approved 300 million U.S. dollars in
financing to support the 1998-2001 investment program of Aguas
Argentina S.A., the sole provider of potable water and sewerage
services for the city of Buenos Aires and 13 surrounding
municipalities.
</P>
<P>
As of December 1998, Aguas Argentinas supplied potable water
and sewerage service to approximately 7.5 million people and
provided sewerage service to almost six million people.
</P>
<P>
The project will expand and improve the services and
rehabilitate the systems in the concession area.
</P>
<P>
Aguas Argentinas has been operating under an exclusive 30-year
concession contract since 1993. The concession stipulates the
eventual expansion of the water system to serve 100 percent of the
population with 100 percent of the collected sewerage treated.
</P>
<P>
The IDB financing consists of a 75-million-dollar "A" loan from
the bank's ordinary capital and a syndicated loan of up to 225
million dollars. Participation in the "B" loan will be sold to
institutional investors or other lenders.
</P>
<P>
ING Barings is acting as the arranger for the first tranche
of the "B" loan, expected to be 120 million dollars, the IDB
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
