<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Civil Servants Continue Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean civil servants Wednesday
 continued with their strike over 20 percent cost of living
adjustment, rejecting the government's offer of 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government has warned that those who continue with the
strike would be severely dealt with, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of civil servants marched through the center of
capital Harare forcing other workers who had turned up for work at
government buildings to join them in the strike.
</P>
<P>
The government Tuesday awarded the civil servants a 12 percent
cost of living adjustment dated back to January 1 this year, and
threatened to take appropriate action against the workers who
would not turn up for work.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean civil servants went on strike last Wednesday to
press the government to award them the 20 percent which has been
paid out in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Staff associations representing civil servants have since last
Friday appealed to the workers to end the action but in vain.
</P>
</TEXT>
