<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean, DRC Presidents Discuss Lusaka Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
and visiting President of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)
Laurent Kabila Wednesday discussed the forthcoming Lusaka summit
on cease-fire in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
After their talks in Zimbabwean capital Harare, Mugabe told
reporters that he has received information reflecting the views of
Rwanda on cease- fire in the DRC, but he was waiting for results
of consultations going on in Zambian capital Lusaka ahead of the
regional summit.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said that the forthcoming summit to prepare the
cease-fire agreement was likely to take place, but chairman of the
summit, Zambian President Frederick Chiluba and others involved
clearly would only go there when ministers had put in place the
arrangements which all parties would have agreed on.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean president said that he and Kabila were studying
a document from Rwanda reflecting their views on the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
"President Chiluba has his own document that reflects our views
which we want to become the basis of the cease-fire," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa had come up with another document on the
cease-fire package which they think would become a complement of
the one prepared by the other allies.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka cease-fire agreement was being drafted to end the
10-month- old war raging in the vast central African country.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire agreement contains inputs from the Southern
African Development Community (SADC), the Organization of African
Unity and the United Nations, as well as from Libya.
</P>
<P>
Kabila arrived in Harare Tuesday and returned home on Wednesday
evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
