<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibian Intelligence Chief Asks for Help in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Namibia's intelligence chief
Wednesday called for public's help in tracing the origins of 57
skeletons which were found in a mass burial site and are believed
to be almost a century old, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The remains were found outside the desert town of Luderitz,
located along southern Namibia's arid Atlantic coastline, said
Peter Sheehama, Director-General of the Namibian Central
Intelligence Agency.
</P>
<P>
Sheehama said there were 30 more such sites in the same area,
all located within huge tracts of land which have been declared
off-limits to the public to safeguard possible diamond deposits.
</P>
<P>
The intelligence chief declined to discuss the possible origins
of the skeletons found in the area or say why he was put in charge
of what may be an archaeological find.
</P>
<P>
It was unclear when the remains were found.
</P>
<P>
Luderitz was the site of a German colonial concentration camp
during the indigenous Herero and Nama rebellions of 1904, during
which an estimated 10, 000 Namas and as many as 65,000 Hereros
were wiped out.
</P>
<P>
German academic Horst Drechsler, citing colonial records, said
that as many as 1,032 out of 1,795 Nama men, women and children in
the concentration camp called Shark Island died between 1906 and
1907, mostly from malnutrition and typhoid.
</P>
<P>
"It's the most likely explanation, that the bodies came from
Shark Island's concentration camp," said Dr. Jeremy Sylvestre of
the University of Namibia's history department.
</P>
<P>
"But... it could also be that these bodies were buried there in
the aftermath of the 1918 flu epidemic, in fear of contamination,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
After Germany was defeated in World War I, South Africa
occupied the territory for more than 70 years. Namibia became
independent in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Leaders Urged To End All Conflicts Before </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Executive Secretary of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) Kaire Mbuende Wednesday
called on African leaders to ensure that all conflicts raging in
the continent are resolved by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
"There is need for African leaders to ensure that all
conflicts, of which there are a total of 11 conflicts on the
continent, to be resolved by the end of the year so that we can
concentrate on development in the next millenium," said Mbuende.
</P>
<P>
He was addressing more than 200 delegates attending the
three-day Zimbabwe National Chamber of Commerce annual congress in
the country's resort town of Victoria Falls.
</P>
<P>
The executive secretary cited the wars in Angola and the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) as some of the conflicts which
posed a challenge to Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said Africa could be optimistic in the case of the DRC in
light of the forthcoming meeting to be held in Lusaka, Zambia, to
seek solutions to the war, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He also spoke on the need to complete the SADC trade protocol
by the end of July this year as it was a means of creating
employment and improving the standard of living of African people.
</P>
<P>
</P>
