<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Enhance Oil Cooperation With Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Jordan will further promote oil
cooperation with Iraq, said visiting Jordanian Minister of Energy
and Mineral Resources Suleiman Abu Ileim here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Abu Ileim made the pledge upon his arrival in Baghdad for a
three-day visit to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Jordan would continue to transport crude oil and derivatives
from Iraq by tankers until mid-2000, and at the same time prepare
to construct a Jordanian-Iraqi pipeline in the future, said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
He added that he would discuss with Iraqi officials on the
possibility for the Jordanian Petroleum Company to develop an
Iraqi oil field.
</P>
<P>
Under a joint Iraqi-Jordanian oil protocol signed last
December, Iraq will provide Jordan with 4.8 million tons of crude
oil in 1999 at preferential prices.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of the 1991 Gulf War, Iraq has provided all
Jordan's needs for crude oil and derivatives under U.N. permission.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced earlier that Iraq and Jordan were preparing for
the final stage to start the construction of an Iraqi-Jordanian
oil pipeline which will be executed on stages.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the oil pipeline will start by laying a
pipeline from Jordan's Zarkaa refinery to the Jordanian-Iraqi
borderline. And Iraq will deliver its crude oil to the borderline
by tankers and pump the oil into the new pipeline.
</P>
<P>
After the pipeline inside Jordan has been laid, the
construction of the pipeline inside Iraq will start soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
