<HEADLINE> S.Leone Rebels Reject Posts Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Foday Sankoh, leader of Revolutionary United Front (RUF), said
he was demanding the vice-presidency in a four-year transitional
government, and at least eight cabinet seats.
</P>
<P>
But the government has ruled out the possibility by saying the
country already had a democratically-elected vice-president.
</P>
<P>
The rebels' refusal to the government's peace terms came quite
of a sudden against the high expectations that a power-sharing
deal between the two sides was close at hand.
</P>
<P>
"The principle of the participation of RUF has been accepted,
but their level of participation is still posing a problem," ,
Togo's Foreign Minister, Joseph Koffigoh, announced Monday before
the adjournment of the peace talks for both delegations return to
Sierra Leone to hold further consultation with the leaders.
</P>
<P>
The rebels' power-sharing demand had been a major hurdle in the
peace talks held in Lome, Togo, between the government and RUT
rebels.
</P>
<P>
The RUF has been demanding certain key positions in a new
transitional government, but the government had formerly insisted
that the rebels must transform themselves into an unarmed
political party and participate in next election.
</P>
<P>
The RUF started war against successive governments in Sierra
Leone since 1991. International community managed a hard-earn
cease-fire on May 24 to usher in the peace talks in Lome.
</P>
<P>
Since negotiations began, the two sides have agreed in
principle on the release of Sankoh, the jailed RUF leader who was
sentenced to death last October on treason charges.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have also agreed on the release of prisoners of
war, and to allow humanitarian relief to be distributed in their
areas of control.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the power-sharing, the thorny issue of the future
role of the Nigerian-led intervention force of the West Africa,
remains to be sorted out. The ECOMOG (West Africa Peace Keeping
Force) has been defending the government against rebel insurgents.
 
</P>
