<HEADLINE> Rwanda, Donors Review Economic Reform Program. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda together with the World
Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) Wednesday opened a
two-day workshop in Kigali to review Rwandan economic reform
programs which began two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan Minister of Finance and Economic Planning, Donald
Kaberuka said as results of its two-year-old Enhanced Structural
Adjustment Facility (ESAF) program, Rwanda has registered
significant economic growth, more money have been located for the
social sector, mainly in education and health, and gross domestic
product has significantly increased, the Rwanda News Agency
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The economy of Rwanda was already experiencing severe economic
 difficulties since 1986. Real sector product had contracted, real
per capita income stood at 231 U.S. dollars, external debt had
accumulated quite a lot and debt service to exports stood at 18.8
percent in 1990, having risen from 7.6 percent in 1996," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
The civil war and genocide in 1994 compounded the situation by
introducing additional dimensions, he added .
</P>
<P>
In addition to the economic hardships, the economy experienced
human catastrophe due to many people were killed and displaced as
well as the reintegration of refugees.
</P>
<P>
"All these problems have implication for programs to revive
economic activities and address poverty," Minister Kaberuka
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
According to Kaberuka, Rwanda still experiences structural
problems relating to the fact that agricultural methods have not
yet changed while the population is increasing, and the growing
external dependence on foreign aid, both in human and material
resources.
</P>
<P>
The seminar organized by the Rwandan Minister of Finance in
conjunction with the Harvard Institute for International
development in the United States, brought together various
stake-holders in the country like civil servants, private sector,
cabinet, parliament, universities, donors and diplomats.  
</P>
