<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Titanic Discoverer Finds Oldest Deep Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 23 (Xinhua) -- American oceanographer Robert
D. Ballard, who located the wreck of the Titanic, and other
explorers have discovered the oldest known shipwrecks off the
coast of Israel, Israeli television reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ballard announced in Tel Aviv that he and his team had found
the wrecks of two ships of more than 2,700 years ago off the
southern port of Ashkelon in the eastern Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
He said they were the oldest shipwrecks to be found in deep
water.
</P>
<P>
The ships, lying more than 300 meters deep under the surface,
each carried hundreds of amphorae filled with wine. As a result of
the cold deep-sea waters and the absence of sunlight, the vessels
are both well preserved.
</P>
<P>
The expedition team said the vessels probably left the
ancient port of Tyre, now in Lebanon, about 750 B.C. bound for
either Egypt or Carthage in modern-day Tunisia. A fierce storm
might be the cause of their sinking, the team said.
</P>
<P>
Ballard told Israel Channel One that the discovery was a
by-product of the search for the Israeli submarine Dakar by
American search and salvage experts in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
Dakar was discovered about 480 kilometers off the Israeli coast
in about 2,926 meters deep under the water last month, 31 years
after it disappeared in its maiden voyage from England to
Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
