<HEADLINE> Ghana Calls for Halt to Gold Sales by IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Ghana said the decision of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to sell gold could have a
crippling effect on gold producing economies, the Ghana News
Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The proposal must be stopped entirely," Ghanaian Minister of
Mines and Energy Fred Ohene Kena said. "The IMF must look at some
other means of supporting distressed countries that depend heavily
on gold to fund their economies instead of selling gold,
especially when the price of the commodity is already down."
</P>
<P>
The IMF proposed selling gold and putting the revenue into a
trust fund and using the interest to fund debt relief and lending
program for poor countries.
</P>
<P>
IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus had assured that it
would make every effort to ensure the sales do not unsettle the
markets.
</P>
<P>
But Kena said that the intended sale must be stopped as
Camdessus' assurance can not be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
The minister said most gold producing economies are already
reeling under the pressure of the recent depreciation in gold
price and can not afford to experience another price fall.
</P>
<P>
Gold prices tumbled recently on the world market from about 269
U.S. dollars an ounce to 259.25 dollars, forcing some emerging
gold mines to live on the edge and totally realign their
production and marketing strategies.
</P>
<P>
The IMF started lobbying for gold sales in 1996, viewing them
as a way to close a funding gap in its program of concessionary
lending for poor countries.
</P>
<P>
It would sell up to 10 million ounces of gold and use the money
as debt relief for the Highly Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the South African gold mining industry has also
warned that the proposed sale of IMF gold reserves will undermine
the current fragile gold market and place further downward
pressure on the price.
</P>
<P>
A partial scrapping of Third World debt was decided at the G-8
meeting in Cologne, Germany, over the weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-23 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Accused of Violating International Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid on Wednesday accused Israel of violating the Fourth
Geneva Convention and international law.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said Israel conducts illegal practices against the
Palestinians in the occupied Palestinian land, including torture,
demolition of Palestinian houses and confiscation of land.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League chief slammed Israel in a speech at the second
international symposium on international law and armament control
organized by the league in tandem with the Egyptian Society of
Criminal Law, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Geneva convention stipulates that the rights of the
civilians under occupation should be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid, meanwhile, underlined that Israel's practices
would only strengthen the resolve of the Palestinian people to
continue struggles till they secure their legitimate rights,
including the establishment of an independent state with Jerusalem
as its capital.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East is going through a critical stage, entailing
sincere commitment on the incoming Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak to advancing the peace process, he said.
</P>
<P>
Barak, leader of Israel's moderate Labor Party, has pledged to
push forward the peace talks with the Palestinians and resume
negotiations with Syria and Lebanon after he won Israel's
elections on May 17.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have made little progress since
1996 when Barak's predecessor, hardliner Benjamin Netanyahu came
to power.
</P>
<P>
Israel's negotiations with Syria and Lebanon were suspended in
early 1996. Israel captured the Golan Heights from Syria in the
1967 Mideast War and set up a so-called security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985. 
</P>
</TEXT>
