<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Combat AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO)
said Wednesday that African governments must immediately declare
AIDS a national emergency and allocate appropriate resources to
combat the spread of the pandemic.
</P>
<P>
WHO African Regional Director Ebrahim Samba said in a statement
that people would take the epidemic seriously when leaders
publicly admitted that it was a problem.
</P>
<P>
"More people will be focused on the problem and international
assistance will be more forthcoming to tame the pandemic. I plead
that this be done without further delay," he said.
</P>
<P>
Africa accounted for 70 percent of people living with AIDS, 83
percent of AIDS deaths and 95 percent of the global AIDS orphans.
</P>
<P>
Samba said the epidemic had become a development issue as it
killed people of the most productive age groups.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the age group mostly affected by AIDS in
Africa was the working group between 20 and 40 years.
</P>
<P>
This pandemic had negatively affected Africa by further
straining on already under-staffed and under-funded health
services, the WHO official said.
</P>
<P>
"Factors accounting for this grim situation include the wide
practice of unprotected sex, high incidence of sexually
transmitted diseases and poor access to care and information," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO to Facilitate Debt Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO)
will facilitate the use of funds from the debt relief announced at
G-8 summit to benefit the needy in Africa, WHO official said in
Harare Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
WHO African regional director Ebrahim Samba said consultations
involving experts from WHO, countries in the region and partners
active in the health and development sectors would be held to
facilitate the process.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the result of this consultation will impact
positively on health indicators such as life expectancy, maternal
and infant mortality, equity and improved access to health
facilities," Samba said.
</P>
<P>
The G-8 leaders agreed to cancel about 70 billion U.S. dollars
debts owed by 36 countries in Africa and Latin America at their
summit held last weekend in Cologne, Germany.
</P>
<P>
The group is composed of the United States, Britain, Italy,
France, Germany, Japan, Canada and Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
