<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Agriculture Harvest up 10% </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 22 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique harvested 1.8 million
tons of grains, in the 1998/99 farming year (from July 1 1998 to
June 30, 1999), about 10 percent more than the previous year,
despite the flood which has affected about 63,000 hectares of farm
land.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Agostinho do Rosario, Minister of Agricultures and
Fishery, attributed the harvest to to improved seeds, enlarged
farming acreage, and the increased number of farmers after the
civil war.
</P>
<P>
Rosario said in a news release here Wednesday that the country
is to export about 160,000 tons of maize and trying to realize
self-sufficiency in rice.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique now has a shortage of only about 67,000 tons of
grain to meet the domestic need, while the figure in 1995 was ten
times more.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the increased agricultural production
has helped enliven the market, adding that the government wishes
to further develop the trade in rural areas, and is planning to
repair roads so to facilitate the circulation of goods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
