<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Spends $1.27bn on Debt Servicing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government spent a
total of 1. 272 billion U.S. dollars on servicing external debt
last year, compared with 1.642 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) Tuesday quoted official
sources as saying that the debt obligations included the principal
repayment, interests as well as penalty and other charges.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 1.272 billion dollars paid last year, 740.5 million
dollars was for principal repayment while interest payment stood
at 527 million and five million dollars was paid as penalty and
other charges.
</P>
<P>
Out of the external debt obligations met last year, 680.2
million dollars was paid to the multilateral institutions, 228.5
million dollars to the Paris Club and 216.3 million to promissory
note holders.
</P>
<P>
The government also paid 127.7 million dollars to the London
Club while 19.8 million was paid to bilateral creditors.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has a total external debt of 28 billion dollars owed
mainly to Paris Club, London Club and multilateral financial
institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
