<HEADLINE> Thailand to Inject Funds Into Property Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government is stepping up
efforts to revive the property market by injecting 50 billion baht
(1.35 billion U.S. dollars) into the sector, the Thai News Agency
(TNA) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The injection would represent the government's new economic
stimulus measure, aimed at boosting demand and supply of local
properties, which would help spur economic activities, TNA quoted
Surapol Kwanchaithanya, managing director of Second Market Credit
Corp., as saying.
</P>
<P>
Surapol said under the new strategic measure, new loans of 45.6
billion baht (1.23 billion dollars) with a fixed annual interest
of around eight percent will be extended to people willing to buy
ready-built houses.
</P>
<P>
The money would come from issuance of bonds by the Government
Housing Bank, which would also be authorized to approve part of
the housing fund itself, and extend the rest to the Government
Savings Bank and commercial banks for lending to their clients,
Surapol said.
</P>
<P>
The bonds will be guaranteed by the Ministry of Finance to
ensure holders of certain returns, he added.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 4.4-billion-baht (118.9-million-dollar) loan
would come from issuance of bonds by Second Market Credit Corp.,
Surapol said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
