<HEADLINE> World Bank Supports Financial Reform in Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank announced on
Wednesday that it has approved a loan of 300 million U.S. dollars
to support reforms in Peru's banking, capital markets, and pension
sectors.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the new loan follows a previous loan totaling 400
million dollars it approved in 1992 in support of financial sector
reform in Peru.
</P>
<P>
In banking, the loan will support the introduction and
implementation of laws and regulations to increase bank
supervisors' ability to identify and correct problems threatening
banks.
</P>
<P>
In capital markets, the loan will support strategies to manage
public debt, and develop the domestic debt market, both of which
allow companies to mobilize resources more easily, stimulate
investment and reduce the economy's vulnerability to external
shocks.
</P>
<P>
Finally, the bank loan will assist managers of private and
public pension systems in their efforts to improve collection of
contributions, expand investment options to increase returns, and
reduce operating costs.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be disbursed in two tranches. The first tranche
of 175 million dollars will be available once the loan becomes
effective. The second tranche of 125 million dollars is expected
to be disbursed nine months following compliance with related
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The loan has a maturity of 17 years, including a 5-year grace
period, and will be made in U.S. dollars at the bank's standard
interest rate for LIBOR-based, single currency loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
