<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Breeds New Pigs Good For Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Canadian scientists at the
University of Guelph have succeeded in creating a new breed of
transgenic pig, considered to be good for the environment, local
newspapers reported here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Named Enviropig, the new breed's manure is reputed to be free
of phosphorus, which promotes an excessive growth of algae in
water sources and robs fish of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
The Globe and Mail newspaper said Wednesday that scientists
were monitoring the progress of three transgenic pigs born to
surrogate sows in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
The piglets look like others of the Yorkshire breed, but inside
the nucleus of each cell of an Enviropig is a strand of DNA that
contains a snippet of mouse and a strain of bacteria.
</P>
<P>
The transgene will allow the Enviropig to produce additional
phytase in the saliva, which releases organic phosphorus in the
animal's gut so that it can be absorbed by the bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
The result is "Environmentally friendly manure," whose
phosphorus level could be reduced by an estimated 20 to 50 percent,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
For each Enviropig, hog farmers could also save as much as 1.70
Canadian dollars (about 1.16 U.S. dollars), because they don't
have to add a phosphorus supplement in feeding them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Delays N.Ireland Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
has put off his trip to Belfast to take part in the Northern
Ireland peace talks till next week, a Downing Street spokesman
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Blair had planned to fly to the province on Thursday, but this
has been delayed and he will instead meet his Irish counterpart
Bertie Ahern in London on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Blair would speak by telephone with Mr.
Ahern later Wednesday and the two would hold further talks in
Downing Street on Friday before deciding when to visit the
province.
</P>
<P>
After their talks in London the two are still expected to go to
Belfast before the June 30 deadline to try to seek a breakthrough
in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The future of the Northern Ireland peace process now hangs in
the balance with only seven days left before the deadline for
agreement on decommissioning and the setting up of an executive.
</P>
<P>
The attendance of the two leaders is believed crucial as the
June 30 deadline for an agreement on implementing the Good Friday
Agreement approaches. 
</P>
