<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNCTAD: World Foreign Direct Investment in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 23 (Xinhua) -- World foreign direct investment
(FDI) inflows in 1998 rose to 644 billion U.S. dollars, 39 percent
more than those in 1997, according to the United Nations
Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD).
</P>
<P>
"The increase was due largely to a substantial increase in
cross-border mega-mergers and acquisitions (M&AMP;A) among developed
country firms," said the UNCTAD in a press release here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The number of cross-border M&AMP;As, most of them in developed
countries, reached to 32 in 1998 from 15 in 1997 and just eight in
1996, UNCTAD said.
</P>
<P>
However, the UN agency said, FDI flows to developing countries
as a whole declined by four percent, from 172 billion dollars in
1997 to 165 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"This decline, the first since 1985, was largely caused by
lower flows to South, East, and Southeast Asia," it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Cabinet Passed Austerity Budget Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 23 (Xinhua)-The Bonn cabinet headed by Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder on Wednesday approved an austerity budget plan
that will cut Germany's spending by 150 billion marks (78 billion
U.S. dollars) in next four years.
</P>
<P>
The " Program 2000", raised by Schroeder's Finance Minister
Hans Eichel, is due to spare 30 billion marks from German annual
budget in year 2000, and the figure will rise to 50 billion in
2003.
</P>
<P>
With the spending cuts, Germany's new borrowing by the federal
government will be accordingly cut by 4 billion marks to 49.5
billion in next year, and will be further reduced to 46 billion in
2001 and 41 billion marks in 2002.
</P>
<P>
The reform package, which will be sent to the parliament on
June 30, is set to help pushing Germany's weak economy by
relieving the burden of the society, declared Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news briefing following the government session in
Bonn, Schroeder said: "with this budget we have a real chance to
support economic growth."
</P>
<P>
"Today's decision by the cabinet is historic and marks a
paradigm change of Germany.we are drawing the consequence of
Europeanization and globalisation," he announced.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, Germany will also cut its corporate tax rate
from the current 40 per cent to 25 per cent in year 2001, giving
business an 8-billion-mark tax relief.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder predicted German economic growth would be improved in
the third and fourth quarter of this year, without spelling out
the overall impact on the country's annual growth rate gross
domestic products (GDP). The government had expected a GDP growth
rate of 1.5 per cent in an earlier forecast.
</P>
<P>
Though the reform plan won applause of German business leaders,
it was attacked by organisations from parliamentary oppositions,
environmental federations and labour unions to Youth Social
Democrats (Jusos), the youth movement of Schroeder's ruling SPD
who said the package would dismantle the social states.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the cabinet's decision, four leading German
business organisations declared to support the reform bill, saying
it would help Germany to attract more investments and to create
more jobs.
</P>
<P>
Hans-Olaf Henkel, the powerful president of German Federal
Association of Industry (BDI), told the Norddeutsche Rundfunk
radio that the major tax reform would by no way have any negative
effect on domestic and foreign investors and job creation.
</P>
<P>
The conservative opposition Christian Democrats (CDU) called
the reform bill a "political broken promise" and a "deception on
voters".
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the CDU Wolfgang Schaeuble said the bill failed to
strengthen Germany's craft for economic growth and job and it was
"fully insufficient".
</P>
<P>
The Socialism Democratic Party (PDS) criticised the reform plan
was a "social unfairness" and would hurt the weak in the society.
</P>
<P>
Bonn's austerity plan includes a cut in state pension growth
rate, health and other social welfare cuts. The pensions will
under the plan grow only by 0.7 per cent in year 2000, equal to
Germany's projected inflation rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
