<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Government Rejects Pro-Human Cloning Advice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The British government Thursday
imposed a moratorium on human embryo cloning by rejecting experts'
advice to allow limited human cloning research.
</P>
<P>
Instead, government ministers are proposing to set up a new
advisory group to investigate the therapeutic aspects of limited
human cloning.
</P>
<P>
In the past several months, scientists have been urging that
cloning of human embryos under 14 days old should be allowed in
Britain, which they believed could lead to revolutionary new
medical treatments.
</P>
<P>
Any form of human cloning is currently banned under British law.
The British government was widely expected to follow the advice
from scientists.
</P>
<P>
But on Thursday, government officials said more time was needed
to look into the implications of such a move, believing more
evidence is required of the need for such research and of its
potential benefits and risks.
</P>
<P>
"The government reaffirms its policy that human reproductive
cloning is ethically unacceptable and cannot take place in this
country." Tessa Jowell, public health minister, has told the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
"However, we recognize that regulations to allow therapeutic
research should be very carefully considered." she added.
</P>
<P>
The British government said that the new advisory group is
expected to begin work during the summer and report early next
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Hopes to Reduce Number of Troops in Kosovo by Autumn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 24 (Xinhua) -- British Defense Secretary George
Robertson said here Thursday that he hoped to cut in half the
number of British troops in Kosovo by autumn.
</P>
<P>
"Our forces will come down by half. It depends on the number of
refugees. I'm hopeful we'll be able to (cut British forces) by
autumn," Robertson told the parliament's defense committee.
</P>
<P>
He said British General Mike Jackson, NATO's Kosovo commander,
was conducting an analysis on how many troops he would need.
</P>
<P>
Britain has 13,000 troops involved in the Kosovo operation. The
troops are now in Kosovo as part of a NATO-led peacekeeping
mission to ensure the safe return of ethnic Albanian refugees
following the withdrawal of Serb troops.
</P>
<P>
Robertson also said the treasury had confirmed it would meet
the cost of the Kosovo war from the government's contingency
reserves.
</P>
<P>
"At the end of May, the costs were 43 million pounds ($68
million), but that does not include replenishment (of military
equipment and weapons) which will be substantial. And that 43
million pounds will go up," he said, adding that the peacekeeping
effort will continue.
</P>
<P>
But the defense secretary declined to estimate the full cost of
replacing equipment and weapons, saying that some items were very
expensive and would bump up the final bill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
