<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Imposes No Restrictions on Shipment Verifications of Strategic Goods: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Regional (SAR) Government has never and will not
impose any restriction on the U.S. agencies conducting pre-license
or post shipment verifications in Hong Kong, a government
spokesman said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the U.S. Senate's passing of the State Department
Authorization Bill on June 22 stipulating in certain provisions
that Hong Kong should be treated like the mainland or denied U.S.
export licenses if the U.S. is denied the right to conduct the
verifications, the spokesman reiterated that the provisions are
unnecessary as the U.S. authority is always free to call on Hong
Kong companies to do the pre-license and post-shipment
verifications.
</P>
<P>
"The Hong Kong provisions in the Bill pay no regard to the
effectiveness of our systems and our status as a separate customs
territory and a separate trading entity.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to maintain an effective and autonomous strategic
trade control system after the reunification, which is regarded as
one of the best in the world by our trading partners. In
particular, our system has stringent special features to guard
against illegal transfer of strategic commodities," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Our system is law based and is totally transparent. We have
been working closely with the U.S. administration, building on the
solid foundation of cooperation as set out in an Agreed Minute
signed by the U.S. secretary of commerce and the secretary for
trade and industry," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He further pointed out that the HK SAR Government will continue
to keep in close contact with the U.S. administration officials
and congressmen to present Hong Kong's system and lobby against
the Hong Kong targeted provisions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
