<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Analyst Jeers at NATO Bombing of Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The robust retreat of Serb soldiers
from Kosovo surprised Western military analysts last week, as
hundreds of tanks and armored vehicles moved out after "the most
precise application of air power in history."
</P>
<P>
The opinion occupied a space of prominence in Thursday's "
National Post" newspaper of Canada.
</P>
<P>
Citing David Rudd, executive director of the Canadian Institute
of Strategic Studies, an article -- entitled "NATO air war far
less successful" -- argued that civilians and city infrastructure
suffered far more than the Yugoslav military in the declared
winning NATO bombings.
</P>
<P>
"There were a lot of tanks that looked as though they were in
very, very good conditions," and "it looks like it wasn't a
military defeat for the Yugoslav army at all," Rudd was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The article said the Yugoslav army seemed far less demoralized,
better organized and much more battle-ready than anyone could have
expected after enduring two months of round-the-clock precision
bombing.
</P>
<P>
It is possible that Yugoslavia's widespread use of inflatable
decoys fooled NATO into claiming kills that never occurred, the
article said.
</P>
<P>
NATO said it dropped more than 20,000 precision, laser-or
satellite-guided bombs on Yugoslavia and insisted a remarkable 99.
6 percent found their targets.
</P>
<P>
But there are growing signs indicating that NATO wasted
expensive, precision-guided munitions on dummy targets, the
article said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
