<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Northern Border Areas Shelled by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Residents in Israel's northern
border areas were instructed to stay in underground bomb shelters
Thursday afternoon after several Katyusha rockets fired from
Lebanon landed in the areas, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The rocket attack, in which no casualties have been reported,
were apparently launched by Hezbollah guerrillas following
reports that one Lebanese woman in south Lebanon was wounded by
shelling fired from the Israeli-occupied border zone.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli shelling was retaliation to previous operations
launched by guerrillas of Hezbollah, or Party of God, on Israeli
positions inside the occupied zone, the radio report said.
</P>
<P>
Saadah Mansour, 40, was wounded when her house in the village
of Kabrikha, just north of the so-called "security zone" carved
out by Israel in 1985 with a claimed aim of preventing
cross-border attacks, was hit by an Israeli shell.
</P>
<P>
She is the sixth Lebanese civilian wounded in Israeli shelling
in the same village in five days. The Hezbollah, who is fighting
to oust the Israeli army and its local militia South Lebanon Army
from the border zone, often fire Katyusha rockets or mortar fire
on northern Israel to retaliate the wounding of Lebanese
civilians.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army ordered residents in Kiryat Shimona and
Nahariyya, two border towns often targeted by Hezbollah
retaliatory rocket attacks, to enter bomb shelters, Israel Radio
said.
</P>
<P>
This was the second time in less than a week that Hezbollah
fired Katyusha rockets into northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
Residents in western Galilee, south of the two border towns,
spent a tense night in bomb shelters Sunday after Hezbollah
slammed two Katyusah rockets there to retaliate the wounding of
three Lebanese civilians in Kabrikha by Israeli missile attack.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak has pledged to withdraw
Israeli troops from southern Lebanon within a year of office
through negotiations with Syria, the main power-broker in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Barak has until early next month to cobble together a
governing coalition, but his assistants said he might form a
government as soon as this weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Orders for Durable Goods Rise 1.4 Percent in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Commerce Department said
Thursday that orders to U.S. factories for durable goods rose 1.4
percent in May, led by a big gains in aircraft, autos and other
transportation products.
</P>
<P>
Orders for big-ticket manufactured goods increased 2.8 billion
dollars last month to a seasonally adjusted 197.6 billion dollars,
the Department reported.
</P>
<P>
The rise followed a steep 2.3 drop in April and a 2.9 percent
gain in March. May's increase was the ninth in the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
Orders for transportation equipment rose a hefty 9.5 percent in
May, following a 12.6 percent decline in April and a 4.7 percent
gain in March. The transportation sector is often volatile from
month to month because it includes such big ticket purchases as
airplanes.
</P>
<P>
May's report said the rebound in transportation orders was led
by a big increase in orders for aircraft and airplane parts. U.S.
automakers are enjoying a good year of sales -- near record
levels.
</P>
<P>
However, if excluding the increase in transportation, overall
orders for durable goods would have fallen 0.7 percent in May, the
biggest decline since a 2.7 drop in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
Financial markets have grown increasingly nervous in recent
weeks that the Federal Reserve will begin raising interest rates
at their meeting next week to slow growth and keep inflation under
control.
</P>
<P>
One of the U.S. industries that has suffered the most from the
global economic turmoil has been steel. But today's report offered
a glimmer of hope that the worst of the crisis may be over.
</P>
<P>
Primary metals, the category which includes steel, rose by 0.7
percent in May, following a 1.4 percent gain April. It marked the
first back-to-back monthly gains in this sector in more than two
years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, orders for industrial machinery declined 2.5 percent
in May, following big gains of 3.6 percent in April and 3.5
percent in March.
</P>
<P>
Last month, shipments of big-ticket durable goods, a good sign
of current demand, also increased 1 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalian Wanda Score Season's First Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Dalian Wanda
scored its first win finally this season as they defeated the
visiting Guangzhou Songri 3-1 in the 10th round of the Chinese
first division soccer league on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Wanda, who won the league champion four times in the last five
years, slided to the bottom on the team standings last Sunday
after losing to Sichuan Quanxing 2-0, keeping their winnless
record intact.
</P>
<P>
The victory was precious for the fallen super 11, who is on the
brink of relegation. And their newly-appointed coach Li Yingfa,
who replaced Xu Genbao to take the helm last month was finally
able to take a sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
But it was the visitors that took command after the start.
</P>
<P>
Formal Chinese national Hu Zhijun put Songri 1-0 up with a long-
range shot in the 15th minute. Wanda's goalie Han Wenhai touched
the ball but failed to stop it since the shot was too powerful.
</P>
<P>
Wang Peng levelled the score 30 seconds after the interval with
a header. Li Ming, Who failed to convert a golden chance to goal
in the 12th minute, made it 2-1 in the 66th minute.
</P>
<P>
Yan Song blasted the ball into the net right outside the area
in the 75th minute to seal the win for Wanda.
</P>
<P>
"I was satisfied with our players' performance," said Li Yingfa.
"But we must maintain the momentum and try hard to win more
matches since we're still in a unfavorable position. This is just
a beginning."
</P>
<P>
But he did not want to predict whether his side could win a
fifth champion since the Chinese professional league was
inaugurated in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"As long as our fans continue to support us, I think we will
not make them disappointed," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the other matches, Tianjin Taida tied Wuhan Heart K 0-0,
Shenzhen Ping'an beat Shandong Taishan 2-1, Chongqing Longxin
ousted Liaoning Fushun 3-1, Sichuan Quanxing edged Beijing Guo'an
1-0, Shanghai Shenhua routed Qingdao Hainiu 2-1 and Shenyang
Haishi drew with Jilin Aodong 1-1. 
</P>
