<HEADLINE> India Has No Intention to Cross LOC in Kargil: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Caretaker Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee Thursday made it clear that India had no intention
of crossing the Line of Control (LOC) in Kargil even as Pakistan
army took logistical control in Gilgit and Skardu regions in
Pakistan-occupied Kashmir (POK) from civil administration.
</P>
<P>
Admitting that Indian troops were facing difficulties in ending
the armed incursions in Kargil sector of Kashmir, Vajpayee told
newsmen here that "even then our intention is not to violate the
LOC and cross over".
</P>
<P>
"Till recently, any suggestion that New Delhi was thinking of
carrying the battle across the LOC was rejected outrightly by
official spokespersons. But for the past couple of days, they have
been saying that such an eventuality cannot be totally ruled out,"
Indian English newspaper 'The Statesman' noted here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"India now appears to be either building up a case for its
forces to cross the LOC, or talking in that vein to build up
international pressure on Pakistan to pull out intruders from
Kargil," it said.
</P>
<P>
Indian Chief of Army Staff V. P. Malik said here on Wednesday
that the possibility of crossing the LOC could be taken up with
the Union Cabinet if the situation warranted.
</P>
<P>
Caretaker Defense Minister George Fernandes Wednesday told
troops and air force fighters posted on alert across India's
Western front to "be ready for a war". "We must teach them a
lesson," he said time and again.
</P>
</TEXT>
