<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Food Agency Issues Urgent Appeal to Feed 800,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World
Food Program (WFP) has issued an urgent appeal for 40 million U.S.
dollars to avert widespread starvation among 800,000 people forced
to flee the continual fighting in Angola, U.N. officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The money will go toward more than 51,000 metric tonnes of
emergency food aid for the most vulnerable people during September
to December, when food shortages are expected to worsen, said the
officials.
</P>
<P>
"Unless food and cash are pledged now and the food delivered
quickly, WFP's aid pipeline will be exhausted by the end of
August," Francesco Strippoli, WFP representative in Angola, said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the people displaced from their homes are out
of the reach of emergency assistance and many of them are already
showing signs of malnutrition due to severe food shortages,
Strippoli said.
</P>
<P>
"Transportation of relief food by road is impossible because of
the upsurge in fighting and the high degree of insecurity in the
country," he said.
</P>
<P>
In Mid-May, WFP said that humanitarian conditions in the
northern city of Malanje, 450 kilometers east of the Angolan
capital of Luanda, had become "extremely worrying." The bombed-out
city is sheltering an estimated 100,000 people displaced by
fighting.
</P>
<P>
The mandate of MOUNA, the previous U.N. mission in Angola, was
terminated last February by the Security Council on the
recommendation of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan who said that
the peace process had collapsed and the country was in a state of
war.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan Government and aid agencies have issued warnings
that the civil war is creating a potential humanitarian
catastrophe with more than a tenth of Angola's 12 million people
displaced and dependent on scarce aid.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is still engaged in talks with the Angolan
Government on the future U.N. presence in the southwest African
country.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council has accused rebel UNITA, the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, of reneging on a 1994
peace accord that called for disarming its fighters.
</P>
<P>
Angola plunged back into civil war in December last year in
the final breakdown of the peace accord when the government
tried to ferret out UNITA fighters but failed to capture all the
diamond-rich areas they control.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
