<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmer Honored as China's First Anti-Narcotics Model (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Liu Tiangui, whose father and son
were both drug addicts, was honored today as the first "Anti-
Narcotics Model" in China.
</P>
<P>
When the National Narcotics Control Commission (NNCC) awarded
Liu the honorary title at a ceremony held here today, Liu, who
arrived in Beijing Wednesday, had driven some 12,500 miles across
the country calling for a crackdown on narcotics.
</P>
<P>
Liu, a farmer from Qingshui Village of Chengdu City in
southwest China's Sichuan Province, witnessed how young people
suffered when they were trying to kick the habit in a mandatory
drug rehabilitation center near his house.
</P>
<P>
"My father was a drug addict before 1949, when New China was
founded," said Liu.
</P>
<P>
Liu, who has become well off since China started its reform and
opening up drive in the 1980s, found that his son had become a
drug addict 10 years ago. Fortunately, Liu managed to wean him off
the habit.
</P>
<P>
"Our country will never be peaceful if narcotics are allowed to
flourish," wrote Liu in a letter to the local public security
bureau.
</P>
<P>
"I decided to be a volunteer urging drug control," said Liu, "
in order to prevent parents being heartbroken and families being
broken up because of narcotics."
</P>
<P>
Liu started a "Long March" against drug in a van on January 20.
Over the past five months he has visited more than 30 big and
medium-sized cities in 28 provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
