<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Fails to Meet Peace Challenges in Africa, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Foreign Minister
Seyoum Mesfin said Thursday that while the United Nations has made
a substantial differences in delivering its mandate in the past
half century, it has fallen far short of meeting the challenges of
peace and security and reducing poverty in Africa.
</P>
<P>
In his opening statement at the Africa regional hearing of the
millennium assembly here, Seyoum asked: "Has Africa received the
requisite solidarity and cooperation from the international
community within the context of the U.N. for it to be able to
overcome its challenges? Has the UN played an effective role for
peace in Africa in conformity with the provisions of its charter
to the same degree that it has in other parts of the world?"
</P>
<P>
Seyoum referred to conflicts in the Horn of Africa, Liberia,
Sierra leone and Angola to interpret U.N. failure in helping
Africa bring peace to the continent.
</P>
<P>
"The genocide in Rwanda which failed to be averted because of
inactions is a reminder of this state of affairs of neglect of
Africa and of the double standards applied to the continent," he
added.
</P>
<P>
On Africa's poverty reducing, he said that "the level of
international cooperation for Africa in this area has indeed been
meager and far from effective."
</P>
<P>
The two-day African regional hearing, organized by the United
Nations Economic Commissioner for Africa, is intended to provide
an open forum for African governments and civil society
representatives to share views and elaborate proposals on the
United Nations in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
About 350 participants will discuss the cooperation for
economic and social development in Africa, and the challenges of
development, peace and security in Africa, among others in the
meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
