<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmer Honored China's First Anti-Narcotics  Model(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Liu showed people posters, video tapes and handed out leaflets
in every place he arrived. Liu also expressed heartfelt resentment
towards narcotics by telling bitter stories of his family.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 people who were receiving drug rehabilitation
have listened to Liu's lectures. And tens of thousands of people
signed on a long banner of Liu's to voice their support for anti-
narcotics struggle.
</P>
<P>
The "Long March" has cost Liu 80,000 yuan (about 9,640 U.S.
dollars) of private savings, 30,000 yuan (3,615 U.S. dollars) of
borrowed money, and some 10,000 yuan (1,200 U.S. dollars) of
donation.
</P>
<P>
"It was a feat worth of appreciation that Liu unswervingly
stick to anti-narcotics promotion at his own expenses while taking
innumerable trials and hardships," said Yang Fengrui, bureau chief
of the narcotics control under the Ministry of Public Security.
</P>
<P>
Liu, however, said that he only did what a citizen should do.
He planned to return home after finishing his promotion work in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Then in August, Liu would start a new march in northwest China'
s Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, Tibet Autonomous Region, and
south China's Hainan Province, Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region before he arrives in Macao when it returns to the
motherland on December 20.  
