<HEADLINE> DPRK, U.S. Talks End in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The two-day talks between the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and the United States
ended here late this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Foreign Minister Kim Kye-Gwan, chief DPRK negotiator,
and Ambassador Charles Kartman, head of the U.S.delegation and
Special Envoy for Korean Peace Talks, declined to make any comment
on the result of the talks.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that Kartman will leave for Seoul tomorrow to
inform the Republic of Korea about the result of the talks.
</P>
<P>
According to sources, the vice-ministerial-level talks between
the DPRK and the ROK, which have been suspended for two days, are
expected to be resumed soon, and the north and the south are
speeding up consultations on the agenda and the time of the second
round of talks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
