<HEADLINE> Pristina Airport Under Russian Peacekeepers' Full Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Pristina airport remains under
the control of Russian peacekeepers, said Colonel-General Yuri
Baluyevsky, head of the Russian General Staff's Operations
Department, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The aerodrome will continue to be under the full control of
the Russian airborne troops and all movements on its territory can
only proceed on permission of the command of the Russian
peacekeeping group," the Itar-Tass news agency quoted Baluyevsky
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under a deal reached last week in Finland's capital of Helsinki,
the Slatina Airport, a few kilometers from the center of Pristina,
capital of the Yugoslav province of Kosovo, will be used by both
Russian and NATO troops.
</P>
<P>
Baluyevsky said a joint air traffic control center would be set
up at the airport to receive both Russian and NATO planes.
</P>
<P>
During the 77-day NATO air campaign against Yugoslavia, the
airport came under repeated attacks and communication and control
facilities were badly damaged, but the runaway remained intact.
</P>
<P>
In another related development, the Russian Aeroflot airlines
announced Thursday that it would resume flights to Belgrade on
Friday, Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
The air service between Moscow and the Yugoslav capital was
suspended following the commencement of NATO air strikes on
Yugoslavia on March 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
