<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Opposes Linking Trade With Labor in WTO Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will propose that members
of the World Trade Organization (WTO) adhere to the agreement on
passing labor issues to the International Labor Organization (ILO)
and not link them with trade issues, a senior Thai Commerce
Ministry official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Thai News Agency (TNA) quoted Director-General of the
Department of Business Economics Karun Kittisataporn as saying
that Bangkok opposes proposals of some western countries that
labor issues be part of the next round of multinational talks on
trade in services, which will be held between November 30 and
December 3 this year in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
Allowing labor issues to be linked to trade would lead to
distortion of the real trade talks, as some countries might use
trade measures to retaliate against others, allegedly not
providing adequate protection for labor rights, Karun said.
</P>
<P>
WTO members must respect the agreement reached at the first
ministerial meeting held in Singapore in 1997 that rules out any
linkage between trade and labor issues and stipulates that labor
issues should be passed to the ILO, he said.
</P>
<P>
Karun said Thailand would propose that the talks be focused on
three main areas, namely to open more market access by lowering
import tariffs and tariff quotas, to cut governments' subsidies
and to deepen the study on genetically modified organisms.
</P>
<P>
The recent meeting of the Group of Eight industrialized nations
discussed linking trade and labor issues at the upcoming global
trade talks in Seattle, but no conclusion was reached due to
differing ideas and views.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister and Commerce Minister Supachai
Panitchpakdi, who is also one of the two candidates for the WTO's
top post, earlier called on the new round of global trade talks to
ensure "balanced prosperity" for the entire international
community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
