<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Banks' Situation Improving: Deputy PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's banking sector have
achieved great improvement when compared to its situation late
last year, Thailand's Deputy Prime Minister and Commerce Minister
Supachai Panitchpakdi said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in response to a report Wednesday by
Moody's Investors Services, a U.S. rating company, saying that
Thai banks are still heavily insolvent in true economic term.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said that Thai banks were now at a much improved
status that could be seen in their abilities to recapitalize in
recent months.
</P>
<P>
It was possible, however, that local banks would have minimal
profits or incur some losses this year due to their cautious
policy to slow down or delay approving new loans to their clients,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Non-performing loans (NPLs) of the local banking system had
also declined when compared to those in late last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier report said that Thai banks' NPLs stood at 42.06
percent of the total loans in April compared to the 46-47 percent
in February.
</P>
<P>
The government's financial sector restructuring program has
helped reduce NPLs of local banks to a great extent, but further
reduction would also depend on improved economic conditions, which
has to take some time, Supachai noted.
</P>
<P>
About Moody's rating, Supachai said Moody's may not base its
latest rating of Thai banks on their most updated development and
data.
</P>
<P>
Moody's had upgraded its ratings of four major Thai banks,
namely Bangkok Bank, Thai Farmers Bank, Krung Thai Bank and Siam
Commercial Bank, from negative to stable on April 29 and from
stable to positive on May 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
