<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Enacts Legislation to Protect Rivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Standing Committee of Beijing
People's Congress today approved regulations on the protection of
rivers and lakes in the city.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that there are more than 30 rivers and man-made
channels in and around Beijing, with a total length of 366 km, and
there are more than 26 lakes in the city with a total surface area
of more than 600 hectares and a total water holding capacity of 12
million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Along with rapid urban development, pollution in these rivers
and lakes has been worsened, according to Yan Changyuan, the chief
of the Beijing Municipal Bureau of Water Conservancy.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations will focus on scientific management of the
water resource in accordance with the overall environment of the
ancient city.
</P>
<P>
The regulations stipulate clear prohibitions concerning the
management of water resources and some requirements on the use of
water source for pleasure-boating.
</P>
<P>
The regulations will come into force October 15.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
