<HEADLINE> Half of Australian Homes Have Computers: ABS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Nearly half of Australian
households have a home computer and the number of Australian
households hooked up to the Internet has soared to 1.3 million, a
five-fold increase in just two years.
</P>
<P>
That means almost one in five homes has Internet access, the
Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said in its social trends
report issued Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The number of households with computers rose from 1.9 million
in February 1994 to 3.2 million last November.
</P>
<P>
And the ABS tips 3.5 million households will have computers by
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
But the growth in Internet access has been even more rapid.
</P>
<P>
In February 1996, just 262,000 households, or 4 percent of the
total, had an Internet connection, but the number rose to 1.3
million by last November.
</P>
<P>
But daily computer usage at home rose by only six minutes to
103 minutes between 1992 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
Canberra residents led Australia in computer ownership, with 66
percent having computers and 28.2 percent linked to the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
