<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Retail Sales Decrease by 10 Percent in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The value of total sales of Hong
Kong in April 1999 is estimated at 14.3 billion HK dollars (1.8
billion U.S. dollars), a decrease of 10 percent compared with the
same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
After discounting the effect of price changes over the period,
the decrease in total retail sales volume was 4 percent, according
to the provisional figures on retail sales released Thursday by
the Census and Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
The 4 percent decline in total retail sales volume recorded in
April represented a notable improvement from the decrease of 10
percent in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Analyzed by type of retail outlets, sales of motor vehicles
continued to show double-digit decrease, by 26 percent in volume
in April 1999 compared with a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
This was followed by sales of fuels (18 percent), and those of
jewelry, watches and clocks, and valuable gifts (13 percent).
</P>
<P>
The retail sales volume of clothing and footwear, however,
recorded a further year-on-year growth of 4 percent in April.
Sales of consumer durable goods other than motor vehicles also
returned to a positive growth, rising by 5 percent in volume
compared with the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
As to retail sales of food, alcoholic drinks and tobacco, there
was virtually no change in volume over the same period.
</P>
<P>
A Government Secretariat spokesman said that the overall
performance of retail sales improved considerably in April 1999,
along with an improvement in the local consumer sentiment and a
further pickup in inbound tourism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
