<HEADLINE> China's First Kentucky Restaurant Reopens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China's first Kentucky Fried
Chicken restaurant, which opened 12 years ago in Beijing, reopened
here today after comprehensive renovation.
</P>
<P>
The fast-food attraction is located at Qianmen, a famous
commercial center in the central part of the Chinese capital. It
still keeps the record as the world's largest Kentucky Fried
Chicken restaurant in terms of its 1,100-sq-m area and ability to
seat 550.
</P>
<P>
The new indoor decorations are in typical Chinese architectural
style, and the layout imitates a typical northern China courtyard
residence.
</P>
<P>
The restaurant is also decorated with traditional Chinese
handicraft works such as kites, paper-cuts and leather silhouettes.
</P>
<P>
Before it closed for renovations, the restaurant had received
13.65 million customers, who ate about two million chickens. On
October 1, 1997, the restaurant's daily sales value reached 445,
000 yuan, setting a record among all Kentucky branches worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Kentucky, a major member of the Tricon Restaurant International
Co., has so far opened 311 branches in 80 cities across China.
</P>
<P>
The company has invested a total of 227 million U.S. dollars in
its Chinese branches, which have 23,500 Chinese employees and have
so far sold 60,000 tons of chicken and made 725 million yuan (
about 87.3 million U.S. dollars) in taxes and profits.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
