<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Arafat Discuss Palestinian-Israeli Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat on Thursday
discussed the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks, Egyptian
information minister Safwat el-Sherif said.
</P>
<P>
El-Sherif, who participated in the meeting, told reporters
after the meeting that Mubarak and Arafat discussed means of
reactivating the Middle East peace process, especially the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's visit came prior to Mubarak's trip to the United
States slated for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
During his upcoming visit to the U.S., Mubarak will brief
U.S. President Bill Clinton on the Arab position on the need to
activate the peace process, implement the agreements signed
between the Palestinians and Israel, and resume negotiations on
the Syrian and Lebanese track in a bid to achieve a lasting peace
in the region.
</P>
<P>
The victory of moderate Ehud Barak in the May 17 Israeli prime
ministerial election has increased hopes for reviving the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Arabs are strengthening coordination and consultations on the
issue. They also hope the U.S., the most influential mediator in
the Arab-Israeli talks, will understand and support the Arab
stand.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Cairo earlier in the day and left here after
the meeting, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
