<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Province Enjoys Surging Private Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Private enterprises, the most
rapidly developing sector in northeast China's Liaoning Province,
have emerged as a new growth point for the provincial economy.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show the province's 1.33 million private enterprises
employ close to 4.5 million people, or 20 percent of the total
provincial workforce.
</P>
<P>
Private investment has soared to 52.44 billion yuan and
accounts for 10 percent of the total registered capital for all
Liaoning enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The sector's 1998 sales volume hit 161.2 billion yuan,
including 88.6 billion yuan in turnover of consumer goods. The
latter figure accounted for 42.2 percent of the provincial total.
</P>
<P>
The sector also contributed 2.5 billion yuan in taxes, or eight
percent of the province's fiscal revenue.
</P>
<P>
"The private sector accounts for 30-50 percent of fiscal income
for most counties, with the figure for a number of counties
exceeding 80 percent," according to one provincial official.
</P>
<P>
The sector is also important channel for absorbing laid-off
workers from state-owned enterprises and has provided reemployment
for over 200,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen provincial government departments launched a united
study of the sector in late 1998. The province is expected to
release regulations designed to accelerate the development of the
private sector in the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
