<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Raises Allowance of Troops in Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Thursday announced big increases in the compensatory
allowance for troops who are serving at an altitude of 12,00O feet
(3,658 meters) and above.
</P>
<P>
Sharif made this announcement while addressing troops stationed
in the Gultari sector, 14 kilometers off the Line of Control (LoC)
in the disputed Kashmir region and northeast of the Kargil sector
where intense artillery shelling has been exchanged across the LoC
recently.
</P>
<P>
The compensatory allowance of the soldiers serving at the
height of 12,000-13,000 feet (3,658-3,962 meters) will be
increased from the present by 40 percent to 50 percent. But For
those who are serving above the height of 13,000 feet, their
allowance level will be increased by 50 percent to 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
Because of the long-running tension with India over the Kashmir
dispute, Pakistan has stationed heavy troops in the mountainous
area where altitudes range from 6,000 feet (1829 meters) to 24,000
feet (7315 meters).
</P>
<P>
Sharif's visit to the LoC is comparable to that of Indian
caretaker Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee on June 13 when he
said India didn't look forward to but never fear a war.
</P>
<P>
During the inspection at the front-line, Sharif renewed his
call for dialogue between Pakistan and India in a bid to defuse
the tension at the LoC.
</P>
<P>
He also visited Skardu Hospital and greeted wounded Pakistani
soldiers there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
