<HEADLINE> Mubarak Requested to Help Solve Pakistani-Indian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan expects Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak to exert efforts to help seek a solution to the
ongoing Pakistani-Indian disputes over Kashmir, a Pakistani
official said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Minister of Religious Affairs Rajah Zafer el Hajj met
with Mubarak after arriving here early in the day to deliver a
message to the Egyptian leader from Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif on the Pakistani-Indian disputes, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
El Hajj was in Cairo to attend an international Islamic
conference organized by Egypt's Higher Council for Islamic
Affairs, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the meeting, el Hajj said Mubarak
"has promised to work on" the issue, a move which the Pakistani
official said gives his country "a sense of assurance."
</P>
<P>
Cairo maintains close relations with both Islamabad and New
Delhi.
</P>
<P>
India accused Pakistani Muslims of infiltrating into the Indian
side of the Line of Control in Kashmir and has been shelling the
hilltops on which it said the infiltrators are entrenched in the
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan calls for a peaceful solution to the problem and sent
its foreign minister recently to New Delhi for talks on the issue,
which ended in failure to persuade India to stop military
actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
