<HEADLINE> Syria, Canada Talk on Peacekeeping on Golan Heights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Syrian Foreign Minister
Farouk al-Shara held secret talks here Wednesday with Canadian
Prime Minister Jean Chretien on a peacekeeping deal on the Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
Canada's "National Post" newspaper said Thursday that the chief
envoy of Syrian President Hafez al-Assad pressed for the staying
of Canadian peacekeepers on the Golan Heights should an agreement
be reached with Israel over the area.
</P>
<P>
Canada has 187 troops among a 1,052-member U.N. peacekeeping
force, established in 1975, to maintain the buffer zone between
Syria and Israel.
</P>
<P>
"I had good talks with the prime minister. I conveyed a message
to him from President Assad," the Syrian envoy was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Syria hopes to get back all the Golan Heights from the Israelis
"so then the Canadians can turn to be a peacekeeping force along
the borders between Syria and Israel", the envoy noted.
</P>
<P>
But Canadian Press Secretary Jennifer Land has made it clear
that Mr. Chretien will not make a commitment on sending
peacekeepers until Damascus and Jerusalem engage in formal peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Farouk al-Shara arrived here on Sunday for a four-day official
visit, which was scheduled to be highlighted by the official
opening of the Embassy of Syria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
