<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Statistics released by the World Energy Studies
Center in London revealed that Saudi oil revenues will increase by
about 8 billion U.S. dollars next year, as compared to 1999.
</P>
<P>
The center, according to Thursday's Arab daily "Al Hayat,"
estimated the average real oil production in Saudi Arabia at
approximately 7.6 million barrels per day this year, dropping
from 8.3 million barrels per day last year.
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- The Sudanese government has decided to postpone the
export of petroleum due to incomplete technical aspects of certain
stations along the 1,600-kilometer-long pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese officials had earlier fixed the end of June as the
commencement date of crude oil exports from the Red Sea port of
Al Bashayer.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- Dubai's gold imports over the last five months
amounted to 199 tons, of which 25.5 tons were imported during
April and March, 22.5 tons in February, and 33.1 tons in January.
</P>
<P>
The Dubai Emirate has one of the most competitive gold markets
in the world.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian Ministry of Agriculture and Land
Reclamation will embark on its new fiscal year's plan next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Director of Agricultural Research Center Saad Nassar disclosed
that the plan envisages the consolidation of agricultural quarantine
stations, anti locust stations throughout the country, and overall
agricultural development in Upper Egypt and Sinai to create job
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has increased its exports by 4.7 percent in the
first quarter of 1999, compared with the same period last year,
Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili has said.
</P>
<P>
The increase amounted to 117 million Egyptian pounds (34.41
million U.S. dollars), mostly in non-oil exports, Egypt's Al-Ahram
daily on Wednesday quoted Gowaili as saying.
</P>
<P>
During the first three months this year, Egypt sold some 2.5
billion pounds (735.29 million dollars) worth of goods to foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Denmark signed here on Thursday an agreement
on encouraging and protecting investments, Egypt's Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Egyptian Minister of State for
Planning and International Cooperation Zafer el-Beshri and Danish
Ambassador to Egypt Erling Harild Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
Denmark has so far invested 69.5 million dollars in 13 joint
ventures in Egypt in industry, agriculture, tourism and services.
</P>
</TEXT>
