<HEADLINE> Lebanese Civilian Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 24 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanese woman was wounded
Thursday in Israeli attacks on her village in south Lebanon, the
Voice of the People radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Saadah Mansour, 40, was wounded when her house in the village
of Kabrikha, just north of the Israeli occupied border zone in
south Lebanon, was hit by an Israeli shell.
</P>
<P>
She is the sixth Lebanese civilian wounded in Israeli shellings
in the same village in five days.
</P>
<P>
Two civilians were wounded in the village on Wednesday and
three on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli attacks came as a retaliation to previous
operations launched by guerrillas of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah,
or Party of God, on Israeli positions inside the occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
A 1996 agreement reached between Israel and Hezbollah after a
16-day Israeli blitz on Lebanon prohibited any attacks from
civilian areas or on civilians.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with a claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting to dislodge Israeli occupation forces
and its ally South Lebanon Army out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
