<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australians Spend 478 U.S. Dollars Each on Gambling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Australian adults spend an
average 736 Australian dollars (478 U.S. dollars) each a year on
gambling, with people in the state of New South Wales the worst
offenders and pokies the most costly temptation.
</P>
<P>
A social trends survey by the Australian Bureau of Statistics
(ABS) said Thursday that in the fiscal year of 1996-1997,
Australians spent 6.5 billion U.S. dollars, or 3 percent of their
household disposable income, on gambling.
</P>
<P>
In the fiscal year of 1972-1973, gambling expenditure, the
amount wagered less than that won, was 1.6 percent of household
income.
</P>
<P>
"However, the recent rapid growth in gambling expenditure has
now begun to level out," the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
New South Wales, of which Sydney is the capital, has maintained
the highest per capita gambling expenditure, which reached 853
Australian dollars (554 U.S. dollars) in 1996-1997.
</P>
<P>
"People spend more time on gaming machines (poker machines)
than any other form of gambling," the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
But lotteries, lotto and pools were by far the most popular
forms of gambling throughout Australia, even though they accounted
for the least expenditure, it said.
</P>
<P>
The highest rates of participation were mostly in the states
where pokies were restricted.
</P>
<P>
Gaming machines came in second in popularity, followed by
racing and casinos.
</P>
<P>
Gambling participation rates increased steadily with age for
both men and women - from around 30 percent for 18-24 year olds,
to more than 55 percent for 55-64 year olds.
</P>
<P>
But rates declined for people aged over 65 years old.
</P>
<P>
Men are more than twice as likely than women to gamble on
racing, particularly in the under-35 and the 65-and-over age
groups.
</P>
<P>
On average, men gambled more frequently than women and spent
significantly more money on gambling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
