<HEADLINE> Sudan Seeking Nigeria's Intervention in Civil War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- A senior Sudanese official has said
that there was an on-going plan to seek Nigerian President
Olusegun Obasanjo's intervention in Sudan's civil war, The Post
Express reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Sudanese Minister of State for External
Relations Reverend Gabriel Rovic as saying Wednesday that Sudan
was looking up to Nigeria to help resolve the conflict with the
rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army led by Colonel John Garang.
</P>
<P>
Rovic who is in Nigeria has already visited Benin Republic,
Gambia, Senegal, Togo and Cote d'Ivoire where he canvassed support
for an end to the on-going civil war.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters in Lagos that "I conveyed special message
from the President of Sudan, General Omar Hassan Al-Bashir to the
leaders of these countries," describing their responses as
"positive".
</P>
<P>
Expressing his optimism on final and decisive peaceful
arrangements in his country, Rovic noted that efforts by Nigeria
and other leading nations on the continent would help to achieve
this.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "our problems with Egypt and the United
States are being addressed," adding: "things are opening up in
relations between Sudan and other countries because we desire
peace."
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, Nigeria has involved in attempts to
reconcile the warring parties in Sudan, resulting in the Abuja I
and II Accords, but the civil war is still going on in the
country. 
</P>
