<HEADLINE> Singapore Share Prices Rise to New Record-High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Share Prices rose to a second
successive record-high close on Singapore Stock Market Thursday on
growing optimism over domestic and regional economic prospects.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) closed 24.26 points
higher at 2,191.73, piercing the 2,200-point resistance barrier in
earlier dealings before slipping back on profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
Total volume shot up to 1,819.82 million shares valued at
2,110.75 million Singapore dollars (1,240.96 million U.S.
dollars). Gainers outnumbered losers by 189 to 177 with 78
counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
IPC topped the volume list with 124.50 million shares changing
hands. It was followed by Hong Kong dollar-listed ICT, which had
65.04 million units traded. GES was the next with 54.69 million
counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
BMT 100 topped the actives chart rising to 81.00 Singapore
dollars with a jump of 100 cents. Jar Mat picked up 78 cents to
finish at 5.50 U.S. dollars. NatElec moved up 55 cents to end at
7.40 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Venture continued to lead the losers of the
day incurring a loss of 100 cents and closing at 14.00 Singapore
dollars. SPH sank 70 cents to finish at 29.30 Singapore dollars.
SIA 200 and SPH 100 retreated 40 cents each to end at 13.20 and
29.20 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market opened on a strong note on
bargain-hunting as investors shrugged off an expected U.S.
interest rate hike and prompted high broad sentiment.
</P>
<P>
They noted that those who sold into the recent upsurge were
getting back into the market.
</P>
<P>
However, late profit-taking eroded early gains amid cautious
sentiment, bringing down STI from the record-setting intraday high
of 2,213.27 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
