<HEADLINE> Nigeria Declares War on Trans-border Bandits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
has said his government would deal decisively with bandits
operating in the border towns, particularly in the northeast and
northwest zones.
</P>
<P>
In his address at the maiden meeting of the National Security
Council held in capital Abuja Wednesday, the president assured
that the government would curb any threats to security in the
villages in border areas where bandits operate.
</P>
<P>
"We have to enforce the confidence of our people and tell the
bandits that we won't fold our hands and let them do what they
like," Obasanjo stressed, New Nigerian newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Following heightened tension in the states bordering Niger,
Chad and Cameroun, Vice-President Atiku Abubakar last week
expressed the government's concern over the consistent threat to
life and property in the border areas.
</P>
<P>
He said Inspector General of Police Alhaji Musiliu Smith and
other security agencies had been mandated to deal with the
situation.
</P>
<P>
The House of Representatives had equally passed a motion
calling for stricter border checks, immediate completion of the
national identify card project and compensation for the victims of
bandits.
</P>
<P>
Last Monday, some bandits allegedly from Chad Republic raided
parts of Borno, Adamaw, Taraba and Pleateau states in northeastern
Nigeria, looting and inflicting injuries on a number of local
inhabitants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
