<HEADLINE> Project Creates Brighter Tian'anmen Square </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Beijing authorities announced
today that the highly successful eight-month renovation project
has created a much brighter Tian'anmen Square.
</P>
<P>
The square is scheduled to reopen to the public by the end of
this month.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman with the Beijing municipal government said that 38
high intensity floodlights have been installed on four new poles
rising to heights of between 29-35 meters.
</P>
<P>
"The new lights will make night skies as bright as day,"
according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that brighter bulbs have been added to the 64
original poles.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of lights are added to decorate trees lining the
bypass, as well as the Great Hall of the People, Monument to the
People's Heroes, the Chairman Mao Mausoleum and various other
famous landmarks.
</P>
<P>
Tian'anmen Square, the largest square in world, covers 440,000
square meters. The famous landmark is fondly referred to as the "
Heart of China" because of its status as the venue for the most
influential events in Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
The existing lighting system was installed during the 1959
expansion project. Complaints that the darkness detracted from
mass activities sparked the ongoing renovation project.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Communist Party Central Committee approved the
project to beautify the square for 50th anniversary ceremonies
marking the founding of New China on October 1, 1949.  
</P>
</TEXT>
