<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Special Envoy Arrives in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations secretary
general's special envoy for East Timor Jamsheed Marker arrived in
Dili, capital of East Timor, Thursday for a three-day visit,
according to Antara News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the Comoro Airport in Dili, Marker held a
closed-door meeting with East Timorese Catholic bishops Carlos
Belo and Basilio do Nascimento, who were about to leave for
Jakarta to attend the June 25-28 reconciliation meeting between
East Timor's warring factions.
</P>
<P>
Marker told reporters that he is visiting East Timor to make
preparations for the direct ballot.
</P>
<P>
"For that reason, I will hold dialogues with various parties
here to obtain inputs useful to the implementation of the ballot,"
he was quoted by Antara as saying.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the postponement of the ballot from August 8 to
two weeks later, he said this has been conveyed by U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan and that he has informed the Indonesian
government about it when he paid courtesy calls to President B.J.
Habibie, Foreign Minister Ali Alatas and Defense Minister/Armed
Forces Chief Gen. Wiranto Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that all parties would understand the
delay, saying the U.N. has to wait until the security in East
Timor is truly conducive to the ballot and the logistics
preparations are adequate.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, spokesman of U.N. Assessment Mission in East Timor
(UNAMET) David Wimhurst said that Marker will meet with local
leaders and visit the districts of Baucau, Suai and Liquica to
observe the preparations for the ballot.
</P>
<P>
"What will be observed and discussed during his stay in East
Timor will be valuable inputs for the U.N. secretary general,"
Wimhurst was quoted by Antara as saying.
</P>
<P>
The August ballot in East Timor will allow the territory's
people to choose whether their homeland should become an
autonomous region within Indonesia or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the U.N., which
still considers Portugal as the administering power of the
territory.
</P>
<P>
Early this year Indonesia announced it would grant East Timor
independence if the people in the territory reject Indonesia's
offer of a wide-ranging autonomy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
