<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Approves Road Loan to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
approved Thursday a 250-million U.S. dollar-loan to help China
build an expressway and upgrade feeder roads in the southwestern
province of Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
ADB said in a news release that the Southern Yunnan Development
Project will support the economic and social development of the
southern part of the province by removing a major road transport
bottleneck.
</P>
<P>
The project, scheduled to be completed by September 2003, will
also facilitate regional cooperation between Yunnan province and
neighboring countries such as Laos, Myanmar and Thailand, ADB
said.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan is one of the poorest areas in China. Average rural per
capita income in the project area is only about 0.32 U.S. dollars
per day, well below the international poverty standard of 1 dollar
per day.
</P>
<P>
According to ADB, the project will construct 147 kilometers of
four-lane toll expressway between two cities, Yuanjiang and Mohei,
in the province besides upgrading about 540 kilometers of feeder
roads.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the project will support institutional development
to improve expressway management and operation, construction
quality, road safety, and project monitoring and evaluation, ADB
said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB loan accounts for 32.5 percent of the estimated total
cost of 770.3 million U.S. dollars for the project. The remainder
of the cost will be borne by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be in U.S. dollars from the ADB's ordinary
capital resources and will have a maturity of 24 years, including
a grace period of four years.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate will be determined in accordance with the
bank's pool-based variable lending rate system for U.S. dollar
loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
