<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Fiscal Mess Needs Drastic Measures: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of India's Finance
Commission A. M. Khusro Thursday warned that India's financial
situation of both the central government and the states could go
out of control if more drastic measures are not taken immediately
to contain mounting deficits.
</P>
<P>
The big deficits in revenue account and consequent fiscal
deficits both at the central level and in states have been a cause
of concern in recent years, he said at the Finance Commission's
meeting in Hyderabad city, 1,499 kilometers south of New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
Revenue deficit of the government has increased from 326.54
billion rupees (8.59 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996-97 to 604.74
billion rupees (15.12 billion dollars) in the revised estimates of
1998-99, he said.
</P>
<P>
Fiscal deficit also rose from 667.33 billion rupees (17.56
billion dollars) in 1996-97 to an estimated 1,037.37 billion
rupees (25.93 billion dollars) in 1998-99, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
