<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hubei Securities Firm Wins Approval to Increase Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The China Securities Regulatory
Commission (CSRC) recent granted approval for Hubei Securities Co.
Ltd. to increase its registered capital from 300 million yuan to
one billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The company based in Wuhan, central China's Hubei Province,
will be the second Chinese securities firm to increase its capital
base. The company has also changed its name to Changjiang
Securities Co. Limited.
</P>
<P>
Xiangcai Securities Co. Ltd. in Hunan Province was the first
securities firm to win CSRC approval to increase its capital base
from 100 million yuan to one billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China's first Securities Law, which is scheduled to enter
effect on July 1, divides securities firms into two categories.
Firms with registered capital of over 500 million yuan fall into
the comprehensive category and are permitted to underwrite new
stocks, while firms with less capital can only operate as brokers
with lower profit levels.
</P>
<P>
CSRC statistics show that China has some 90-odd professional
securities firms and an additional 230 firms engaged in part-time
securities business. An overwhelming majority of the firms
registered capital well below 500 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
CSRC officials have repeatedly asserted that enforcement of the
law will be a gradual process, and most securities firms have been
under pressure to expand their capital bases.
</P>
<P>
The CSRC is currently reviewing capital expansion applications
submitted by six firms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
