<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Paying Fliers Take Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Increasing numbers of China's air
passengers are paying their own fares rather than being sponsored
by enterprises or organizations, which is attributed to the
country's rapid economic growth and rising incomes.
</P>
<P>
 A recent survey revealed that this new breed of air traveler
accounts for 43.88 percent of the total, compared to 31.67 percent
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
 The passengers are mainly middle-aged people and youngsters,
who account for 43.38 percent and 46.92 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
 It also revealed that passengers on business trips make up
the majority of the civil aviation's customer base , accounting
for 58.53 percent.
</P>
<P>
 The survey, conducted by the China Civil Aviation Association,
questioned passengers flying between October 1998 to April 1999
and covered all large and middle-sized airlines and airports,
whose annual handling capacity is over one million persons.
</P>
</TEXT>
