<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Prefers Dialogue for Resolving Crisis With India: Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz reiterated Thursday that his country prefers dialogue
for resolving the current crisis in the disputed Kashmir area.
</P>
<P>
During a briefing with a group of Islamabad-based Chinese
correspondents, Aziz expressed the hope that the Indian side will
"respond positively" to the dialogue proposal he had made during
his latest visit to New Delhi and will come to the negotiating
table in a bid to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said it is "sad" that the Indian side had
rejected his proposal.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the G-8 summit this week also called for
resumption of Pak-India bilateral dialogue in the spirit of the
Lahore Declaration which was signed by the prime ministers of the
two countries in February this year.
</P>
<P>
The G-8 also urged both India and Pakistan to stop hostility,
stop fighting and respect the Line of Control (LoC).
</P>
<P>
Aziz said the G-8 proposal concerning the current crisis in the
region was the same as made by Pakistan. "Pakistan is ready to
respond to the G-8 proposal," he added.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that the tension on the LoC has been
escalated by India because of its heavy deployment of armed forces
and weaponry for "political and some other reasons."
</P>
<P>
Aziz is of the view that the current armed conflict in the
Kargil sector on the LoC is basically the reflection of the
long-running Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
"When the Kashmir problem is solved, issues like Kargil will
not happen," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question as how to assess the prospect of the
ongoing crisis in Kashmir, Aziz said, "We have, of course, been
ready in case there is any increased level of activities which
threat our security. We have to defend ourselves."
</P>
<P>
"But we prefer dialogue as it has also been suggested by the
G-8 group," said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
To another question concerning the alleged "infiltration" by
Pakistan, Aziz said, Pakistan has never crossed the LoC. It is
India which has violated the LoC three times since 1972, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan is not calling them infiltrators, they are freedom
fighters. When the U.N. is not giving them the right of
self-determination for 50 years, and the Indians also denied that
right, they have to fight for their right," said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the ongoing visit here by General Anthony Zinni,
commander in chief of the U.S. Central Command, Aziz said, Zinni
would be concerned that the current situation should not get out
of control, he would advise both sides to restraint, as "we are
exercising in any case."
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that the current crisis could be
resolved if the two sides show their commitment to respecting the
LoC.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Kashmir, Aziz proposed that Pakistan and India
hold "a meaningful discussion" on it. The Kashmir issue, he said,
"needs a solution, not a temporary solution, but a sustainable
solution."
</P>
<P>
"We are ready for a U.N. role, we are ready for any mediator,
we are ready for good office," Aziz stressed.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that once the current crisis is resolved,
Pakistan and India will be able to discuss the core issue of
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question, Aziz said that "nuclear weapons are
basically a deterrent, they should never be used. And because of
the nuclear weapons, India will not expand the theater of war, and
there is no occasion to use it."
</P>
<P>
"Both India and Pakistan have to prove to the world that we are
responsible nuclear powers," said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
To another query concerning the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty
(CTBT), Aziz said Pakistan's position on signing the CTBT, as
announced by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif at the U.N. General
Assembly last September, is that Pakistan will sign the CTBT by
September this year in an environment which is free of coercion
and pressure.
</P>
<P>
He noted the precondition to that is both the economic and
military sanctions imposed on Pakistan must be removed.
</P>
<P>
However, the foreign minister also said that if India conducts
fresh nuclear test, "we have to reserve our right to respond."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
