<HEADLINE> Pak PM Renews Talks Offer to India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 20 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Thursday renewed his offer of talks to India for defusing a
war-like situation along the Line of Control (LoC).
</P>
<P>
"I invite the government of India to choose the path of
rationality and understanding," Sharif said while addressing the
troops at the height of 11,600 feet in Gultari sector along the
LoC.
</P>
<P>
Efforts should not only be made to put out the raging fire at
Kargil but also to extinguish the bigger fire which has now
brought the whole of Kashmir under its grip, he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged India to de-escalate the situation because problems
could not be solved through war and conflict.
</P>
<P>
"Time and again, we tried to tell India that we want peace," he
said, adding that was the reason "we had extended an invitation to
India for talks."
</P>
<P>
"If there is war or if the present confrontation continues on
the borders, it will bring so much devastation, the damage of
which will never be repaired," said the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
However, Sharif lauded the troops' efforts to effectively stop
the  Indian "incursions" along the LoC. "You are not fighting the
battle alone, as the entire nation is behind you," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Kargil sector, he said, "The occupation of Kargil
peaks by freedom fighters is the fruit of their 11-year-old
struggle for freedom."
</P>
<P>
It is the outcome of the sacrifices rendered by thousands of
Kashmiri brothers and sisters, he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the presence of 600,000 Indian troops in the "held"
Kashmir, the spirit of the freedom fighters could not be dampened,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he was confident that the Kashmiris would soon get
their right of self-determination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
