<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ministry of Railways to Promote "Arrival in One Day" Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Railways plans
to introduce a scheme for the rest of this year which will ensure
trains to and from major cities arrive in one day, in a bid to
shorten the time of some 2,000-km railway journeys.
</P>
<P>
By further improving the dispatching, the scheme is expected to
enable the original 30 to 35 hour journeys, starting from Beijing,
Shanghai or Guangzhou, to be completed in one day and one night,
to 21 to 22 hours, according to Li Zhonghao, vice director of the
ministry's Science and Education Department.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that the scheme will greatly improve the railway's
ability to compete with airlines and road transport companies on
the medium-range and long-distance transportation market.
</P>
<P>
China's railway departments succeeded in speeding up trains on
three backbone railway routes: Bejing-Shanghai, Beijing-Guangzhou,
Beijing-Harbin in April, 1997 and October, 1998, respectively,
from below 100 km per hour to more than 100 km.  
</P>
</TEXT>
