<HEADLINE> East Nile States Form Coop Panel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Minister of Water
Resources Shiferaw Jarso said East Nile countries comprising
Sudan, Egypt and Ethiopia have formed a joint cooperation
committee mandated to ensure fair utilization of the Nile waters
for carrying out development works.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian herald Thursday quoted Shiferaw as saying here
that the committee will meet at least once every month to discuss
matters by consulting the authorities of the three countries.
</P>
<P>
Shiferaw also said Ethiopia has been elected to chair this
technical committee.
</P>
<P>
Last month, 10 Nile River riparian states held a two-day 7th
conference of ministers of water affairs in Addis Ababa. The 10
Nile riparian states are expected to sign a final framework
cooperation agreement by the year 2002 at its 10th conference.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian minister said that conditions have now been
created, following cooperation agreements made with Nile Basin
countries, which allow Ethiopia to carry out development
activities on a wider scale by harnessing hydro-electric power and
diverting the waters of the Nile for irrigation and similar
activities.
</P>
<P>
He said, Ethiopia has water potential capable of generating
25-30 thousand megawatt of hydro-electric power, adding that the
country has harnessed at present only 370 megawatt.
</P>
<P>
He added that comprehensive development and investment plans
have also been prepared by the Nile Basin countries while projects
have been drawn in a very unambiguous and transparent way
sufficient to build mutual confidence among riparian states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stock Investors Surging in Chinese Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The number of stock investors has
been surging by more than 4,000 a day in the Chinese capital for
the past three days as a result of the bullish market.
</P>
<P>
The number in the city had climbed to a total of 1.52 million
by June 23.
</P>
<P>
A growing number of Beijing residents have opened stock
accounts since May 19 when the stock market started to take an
upward trend. They opened 2,200 stock accounts in the first week,
4,500 in the second, 6,200 in the third, 7,400 the fourth and 13,
000 in the fifth, according to Zhang Jinglin, vice-president of
the Beijing Securities Registering Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said his company has opened new service windows, extended
service hours, and even added mobile service outlets to cope with
the rocketing number of new investors.
</P>
<P>
"Some stock companies are trying to lure more investors to open
trading accounts by waiving the accounts opening fee," said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Training schools and paging companies are also reaping fat
profits from the surge in stock investors.
</P>
<P>
"We offer classes in stock investing once a week now, compared
to once in two or three weeks in the past, and 80 percent of our
students are new stock investors," according to the president of
the Super-wave Securities School in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese stock market has ridden the wave of an upward trend
since May 19, and the Shanghai Composite Stock Index set a new
high of 1,654 points today, breaking Wednesday's record of 1,606
points.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
