<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Legislator Explains Draft Interpretation of Basic Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- It was both necessary and
appropriate for the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress (NPC) to interpret relevant articles of the Basic Law of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), according to
Qiao Xiaoyang, vice-chairman of the Legislative Affairs Committee
of the NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the ongoing 10th meeting of the NPC
Standing Committee members which opened Tuesday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
He said that HK SAR Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa presented a
report to the State Council on May 20. Tung asked the Central
Government to help solve the problems occurred in implementing
relevant articles of the Basic Law, in accordance with the right
granted by Article 43 and Article 48 (2) of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The State Council then put forward a proposal to the NPC
Standing Committee, seeking for interpretation of Article 22 (4)
and Article 24 (2)(3) of the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
Qiao said that according to a meeting of chairpersons of the
NPC Standing Committee, issues mentioned in the proposal were
related to interpretation of some relevant articles of the Basic
Law made by the HK SAR Court of Final Appeal in a judgment
announced on January 29, 1999.
</P>
<P>
He noted that according to Article 158 (3) of the Basic Law,
the Court of Final Appeal should ask the NPC Standing Committee
for interpretation of relevant articles before giving the final
judgment if the case was about affairs governed by the central
authorities or about the relations between the Central Government
and the HK SAR government, and if the interpretation would affect
the ruling.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the HK SAR Court of Final Appeal did not
request the NPC Standing Committee to interpret the articles, and
its own interpretation ran counter to the legislative intent of
the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
According to the provisions of the Constitution and Article 158
(1) of the Basic Law, it was both necessary and appropriate for
the NPC Standing Committee to interpret relevant articles of the
Basic Law in order to ensure correct implementation of the Basic
Law.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of NPC chairpersons therefore has advanced a draft
interpretation and asked advice from a commission on HK SAR Basic
Law under the NPC Standing Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0167 </DOCNO>
