<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Widens Traders' Qualification Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China has decided to lift the
restrictions on who can take the qualification test to become a
certified trader and thrown it open to anyone, instead of only to
foreign trade companies, in a bid to meet the increasing demand
for such personnel, the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Department of Personnel of MOFTEC told
Xinhua that "certified traders" are now in short supply in China
since more and more companies have gained the right to do import
and export business.
</P>
<P>
In the past couple of years, China gave the authority to carry
out foreign trade not only to actual trading companies, but also
to industrial enterprises, foreign-invested companies, private
firms and research institutes.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, certified traders with a basic knowledge and
experience of foreign trade business are now in great demand,"
said the official, who declined to be identified.
</P>
<P>
A certified trader can engage in not only commodities trade,
but also service and technology trade. They can participate in the
negotiations for imports, exports, contracting and bidding, said
the official.
</P>
<P>
Now anyone, including those working in foreign trade companies,
students, companies with import and export licenses and research
institutes, are allowed to participate in the test, which will be
held annually from this year.
</P>
<P>
Those who pass the test will be issued with a certificate
effective for five years. Certificate holders may find it easier
to get a job with relevant companies, said the official.
</P>
<P>
China introduced the test in 1989. A total of 230,000 people
have applied but only 60,000 passed the test and were awarded with
certificates. Most of them are now working in China's foreign
trade companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
