<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Citizens Pawn Possession To Buy Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- As China's stock market enjoys a
bull run these days, people in Shanghai, the largest Chinese city
where one of the country's two bourses is located, have flocked to
the local pawn shops with jewelry and other valuable possessions
to swap in cash to enable them to buy shares.
</P>
<P>
"The stock market is in the middle of a golden time now, and I
need money badly to buy more shares. I can get the pawned items
back after selling my stock at a higher price, and it will turn
out to be a good deal," said a man who sent jewelry and even his
wristwatch to a pawn shop.
</P>
<P>
According to Wu Xianda, manager of the Shanghai Hualian Pawn
Shop, the shop's business volume has surged in the past few days.
At its peak the shop loaned more than 300,000 yuan (about 36,000 U.
S. dollars) in a single day, 50 percent more than the usual figure.
</P>
<P>
Apart from jewelry and watches, items Shanghai citizens pawned
included motorcycles and the title deeds of private houses, said
Wu.
</P>
<P>
There are now a total of 12 pawn shops in Shanghai, which
usually offer one month long short term loans worth some 50 to 80
percent of the items' value.
</P>
<P>
Many other Shanghai residents also sought loans from banks with
their fixed deposit certificates as security. According to
statistics from a local commercial bank, the number of such loans
it handled since early March has soared to 2,000 a month from the
previous 1,000.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that most of the new loans have flowed into the
stock market," said a bank official.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Stock Exchange's composite stock index Wednesday
exceeded 1,600 points, reaching a new historical high.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
