<HEADLINE> Sweden Boost Hopes of Qualifying for Second State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PORTLAND, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Sweden boosted their hopes of
qualifying for the second round with a 3-1 win over Australia at
Washington on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Entered entered the match against Australia as the bottom team
of Group D as they lost their first match 2-1 to China at San Jose.
Australia tied for the second place after a frustrating 1-1 draw
with Ghana.
</P>
<P>
In Wednesday's match, Sweden found the net first, scoring at the
ninth minute. Jane Tornqvist headed home a well-placed corner kick
from Malin Andersson to give Sweden an early lead.
</P>
<P>
At the 14th minute, Andersson nearly added a goal when her
attempt from outside the penalty area sailed just over the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
Hanna Ljungberg finished a cross from Kristin Bentgsson in the
21st minute. Bengtsson's pass barely found its way past the
Australia's goal-keeper. Ljungberg easily tapped it into the open net.
</P>
<P>
Julie Murray kept Australia in the match when she stole the ball
from a Swedish defender and the rushed onto a goal and slotted home
at the 32nd minute for her second goal in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
But Australia's hopes of getting an equalizer were dashed by
Ljungberg at the 65th minute when she sealed the 3-1 victory for the
Swedish team.
</P>
<P>
With only one point from two matches, the Australian team face
long odds of advancing. They must beat Group D leaders China on
Saturday and have the right results fall into place in the match
between Ghana and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Australia making the quarterfinals would clarify the race for
the 2000 Summer Olympics berths. As the host to the Sydney Olympic
Games, the Australian team have an automatic bid, seven other places
in the field remain. The least scenario for determining the Olympic
participants would take place if Australia advance. 
