<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan's Parliament Fails to Pass No-Confidence Vote in Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan's parliament failed to
pass a no-confidence vote in the government Thursday after
lawmakers had refused to adopt amendments to the national budget,
a news report said.
</P>
<P>
The government called for the no-confidence vote after the
parliament refused to adopt the amendments Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the constitution, a two-thirds majority is needed to pass
a no-confidence vote in the government. If the motion had been
approved, President Nursultan Nazarbayev would have had to order
the government to resign or dissolve parliament.
</P>
<P>
With the vote's failure, the budget amendments are adopted
automatically.
</P>
<P>
The amendments call for a reduction of revenue by 11.5 billion
tenge (about 87.8 million U.S. dollars) to 278.4 billion tenge (
about 2.1 billion dollars) and a cut of 18 billion tenge (about
137.4 million dollars) in expenditure to 338.8 billion tenge (
about 2.6 billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
