<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Confident of Meeting Population Control Goal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China has expressed full
confidence in meeting its goal of keeping population within 1.3
billion by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Looking at the progress being made toward this end, we have no
doubt that the target will be hit," said Yang Kuifu, deputy
minister in charge of the State Family Planning Commission (SFPC)
here today.
</P>
<P>
Yang is in this coastal city in northeast China attending a
seminar on population control. He said the conclusion was drawn
following comprehensive study based on a recent sample survey by
the State Statistics Bureau (SSB) and on thorough consideration
that some local officials might have concealed accurate population
figures.
</P>
<P>
Population control is a vital part in China's family planning,
a basic state policy. The population control goal is set in line
with the most populous country's social and economic development
program. Total population in China stood at 1.248 billion at the
end of 1998, according to the SSB.
</P>
<P>
The figure includes an increase of 11.84 million, up 0.95
percent from the previous year, and after subtracting the number
of 8.07 million people who died in the year."This was the first
time China's population growth rate was below one percent since
the 1970s," said Yang.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that population growth continued to slow
down in the first half of this year, and many experts believe that
China will probably add another 11 or 12 million people this year
to bring the total population to around 1.26 billion.
</P>
<P>
Average reproduction rate of Chinese women at child-bearing age
has dropped from 1970's 5.8 to two in 1997, placing China among
the low birth rate countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in population growth is also attributable to a
gradual change in people's attitudes towards having children.
People used to be obsessed with a long-standing concept: more
children, more happiness.
</P>
<P>
From the 1st century A.D. to 1949, China's population increased
ten-fold to reach 500 million. But the figure astonishingly
doubled in the following 30 years.
</P>
<P>
In 1982, China introduced the One-Child policy (one child per
couple), with some exceptions in rural areas which means that some
farmers can ask permission to have a second baby.
</P>
<P>
Real progress in keeping the count down were first seen in
cities, where the people are better-off and life style is more
modern, and where some couples are actually not inclined to have a
baby anyway.
</P>
<P>
According to Yang, major cities in ten eastern provinces have
actually reported a zero growth rate of population.
</P>
<P>
The major obstacles are in rural areas, where 70 to 80 percent
of the Chinese people live. Serious consideration is given in
these places to maintaining traditional philosophies such as the
continuation of the clan which can only be realized by a male
child. Its interruption would be a catastrophe for a family.
</P>
<P>
What follows does not usually have a happy ending. Families
with more children tend to be more poverty-stricken because
feeding them is a difficult job, not to say their schooling.
</P>
<P>
Today, however, the situation has changed in many areas. "In
our village, 69 women are qualified to apply to have a second baby
in accordance with the government policy, but only nine have
expressed any interest," said Xue Yuhuan, a villager of Qidingshan
village in coastal Liaoning province.
</P>
<P>
In another case, Yao Anhua, a farmer in the Baise Prefecture in
southwest Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, said that he did not
want to have more children. Instead, he would place top priority
on his kid's education which he said would help the child find a
well-paid job in the future.
</P>
<P>
According to Chao Jingchun, a member of the China Population
Society, the biggest change in attitudes is because an increasing
number of people realize that the government's targets are
actually in their personal interests.
</P>
<P>
The development of a socialist market economy, the mounting
media campaigns, and the improvement of the social welfare system,
helped in transforming people's way of thinking, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yang added that another very welcome measure has
been the introduction of a flexible policy which allows farmers to
freely choose contraception methods.
</P>
<P>
"I have not heard of a single case of a forced abortion in my
village for many years," said Zhao Guiqing, a village birth
control official.
</P>
<P>
China has only seven percent of the world's arable land, but
has to feed one fifth of the world's population. And it faces a
shortage of energy and environmental deterioration. "So, it has no
choice but to control population growth," said Tian Xueyuan,
director of the Population Institute of the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"If there is a population explosion in China, the whole world
will be affected," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0180 </DOCNO>
