<HEADLINE> S.Lanka, Sweden Sign Contract on Hydropower Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Ceylon Electricity
Board (CEB) Thursday signed a contract with a Swedish company for
constructing an underground hydropower project in the island
country.
</P>
<P>
The Skanska International Civil Engineering AB of Sweden has
been awarded the contract for construction of a waterways and
power station of the Kukule Ganga Hydropower Project, located
about 80 kilometers southeast of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The contract, valued at 3.9 billion rupees (55.7 million U.S.
dollars), is one of the six main contracts for implementation of
the whole project which will be funded by the Overseas Economic
Cooperation Fund of Japan (OECF) and CEB, said CEB Chairman Arjun
Deraniyagala.
</P>
<P>
The main civil construction works will begin in July this year
and the project will be completed in December 2002.
</P>
<P>
"The Kukule power plant will have a daily regulating pond and
the annual average generation is expected to be at 317 million
units," said Deraniyagala.
</P>
<P>
The project is estimated to cost 15 billion rupees (214.2
million dollars). The OECF will provide a loan of 12.8 billion
rupees (182.8 million dollars), while the CEB will meet the
balance of 2.2 billion rupees (31.4 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government has decided to observe 1999-2009 as a
decade of power development.
</P>
<P>
The 10-year power development program, estimated to cost 200
billion rupees (2.94 billion dollars), is designed to provide
every household with electricity and increase the national power
grid in order to cater to upcoming industries.
</P>
<P>
Only 52 percent of Sri Lankan households now have access to
electricity. The power shortage has severely restricted the scope
of people's life and industrial development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
