<HEADLINE> Russia A Big Step Towards Quarterfinals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PORTLAND, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Russia moved a big step towrads
the quarterfinals of the third Women's World Cup with a comfortable
5-0 victory over Japan here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian team, World Cup new-comers who were beaten 2-1 by
defending champions Norway in their first ever World Cup match,
dominated the match against Japan at Civic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
Irina Grigorieva made three assists in the match, helping her
teammates Larissa Savina, Olga Letuchova to score three goals.
</P>
<P>
The first goal came at the 29th minute when Grigorieva sent
Savina clear while the latter beat the Japanese goal-keeper with a
right-foot shot.
</P>
<P>
The Russian team enjoyed a greater advantage in the second half
as Letuchova scored twice at the 52nd and 90th minutes respectively.
Natalia Karasseva and Natalia Barbachina each added one goal.
</P>
<P>
The Russian team are too strong physically compared with their
Japanese opponents. The Japanese team, with high spirit though,
could not follow the Russian team's pace and unable to explore the
Russian defense line.
</P>
<P>
Japanese coach Satoshi Miyauchi said after the match:"We had a
tough time scoring, but I don't see it as a problem because we took
a lot of chances and played our best."
</P>
<P>
"The Russians were definitely stronger, but it is something we
are going to have to work on." said Miyauchi.
</P>
<P>
Russian coach Yurii Bystritzkii said:"We didn't take the loss to
Norway too dramatically. It was more of an incentive for us to get
to the quarterfinals."
</P>
<P>
Bystritzkii said he was not surprised by the big-margin
win:"I've known this team for a very long time and I know they
score, so I am not surprised about this result. But I am still not
satisfied because we missed many good chances."
</P>
<P>
Grigoreieva, who was named the best player of the match,
said:"The opening match was very tense, but today's second half
showed our improvement and composure since then." 
</P>
