<HEADLINE> China to Build Hongshui River Hydropower Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Construction of a hydropower
station on the Hongshui River in south China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region will begin in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Longtan Hydropower Station, in Tian'e County, will be a key
project for the development of the Hongshui River hydropower
resources.
</P>
<P>
The station, with an estimated cost of 28.3 billion yuan, will
have a total generating capacity of 4.2 million kilowatts and will
generate 15.7 billion kwh of electricity annually.
</P>
<P>
The project will rank only behind the massive Three Gorges Dam
Project on the Yangtze River in terms of generating capacity.
</P>
<P>
A team of 16 hydroelectric specialists and economists appraised
and presented research papers covering seven major construction
topics on the project in Beijing recently.
</P>
<P>
The China National Power Corp. initiated the projects and has
signed agreements with the Guangxi Power Co., Guangxi Development
and Investment Co. and Guizhou Province to facilitate construction.
</P>
<P>
Preparatory work will be completed at an estimated cost of 500
million yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
