<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indonesia's Political Struggle Shifts to Upcoming Presidential Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- With the Indonesian Democratic
Party of Struggle (PDI-P) led by Megawati Soekarnoputri certainly
to win the June 7 general election, the political struggle has now
shifted to the presidential election later this year.
</P>
<P>
Despite winning the general election, Megawati can not
automatically become president because Indonesia's national leader
is elected by the 700-member People Consultative Assembly (MPR),
comprising 462 elected legislators, 38 military appointees and 200
selected regional and group representatives.
</P>
<P>
Although PDI-P will likely win the parliamentary election with
about 40 percent of the votes, it is not enough for her to control
the 500-seat House or MPR.
</P>
<P>
Horse-trading and coalition building has already heated up
among the political parties to prepare for the November
presidential election. The National Awakening Party (PKB) threw
its weight behind Megawati while the United Development Party
(PPP) supported incumbent President B.J. Habibie for the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
The two Muslim-backed parties are expected to play a major role
in shaping the next government as no single majority will come out
of these elections. So far, the PKB ranks third in the provisional
tally, while the PPP runs fourth.
</P>
<P>
PKB leader Taufikurrahman Saleh Wednesday said the party will
drop patron Abdurrahman Wahid from its candidacy and will instead
support Megawati.
</P>
<P>
PPP leader A.M. Saefuddin said that his party will throw its
support behind Habibie in the MPR general session in November.
</P>
<P>
Another Muslim-backed party, the National Mandate Party (PAN),
now fifth in the provisional tally, has expressed its support to
Megawati.
</P>
<P>
PAN General Chairman Amien Rais said that he had buried his
dreams of becoming president and implied that the president's
gender was not of concern to PAN.
</P>
<P>
The powerful Indonesian Armed Forces (TNI) has repeatedly
reiterated that TNI was hoping that the best citizen in the state,
"either a man or a woman," would be elected president.
</P>
<P>
However, Megawati is facing a bumpy road to the presidency as
some Muslim groups have aired their disagreement over the
possibility of a female president in the world's largest Muslim
country.
</P>
<P>
PPP has recommended that only a male Muslim candidate be
eligible for the presidency. Some public figures have also stated
that a woman should not be permitted to lead the country.
</P>
<P>
At a discussion in Jakarta on Wednesday, Emil Salim, who served
as environment minister under former president Soeharto, said
Megawati has more right than any other contenders to become the
country's next president because her party gained the lion's share
of votes in the election.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of volunteer election monitors, mostly women,
Wednesday staged a protest outside the House of Representatives,
condemning Muslim groups that claim Megawati can not become
Indonesia's next president because she is a woman.
</P>
<P>
The Movement for Anti-Violence Against Indonesian Women Tuesday
called on the public to accept the results of the election and the
presidential election. The group of 50 non-governmental
organizations said they suspected efforts to prevent Megawati from
running for presidency.
</P>
<P>
The Forum of National Communications for Alumni of the
Nationalist Student Movement Monday declared its support for
Megawati.
</P>
<P>
As no single party is expected to win the majority of votes in
this general election, many fear that the Golkar Party could bribe
unelected (and many elected) members of the MPR to ensure that
Habibie, its sole candidate, is elected for another term.
</P>
<P>
Golkar Party has also indicated that it may review the
nomination of Habibie if its approaches to other political parties
do not produce positive results.
</P>
<P>
With fears of a deadlocked presidential election looming,
Chairman of the Nahdlatul Ulama Muslim organization Abdurrahman
Wahid last week suggested a separation of power between the head
of government and the head of state.
</P>
<P>
He said the head of state should only perform protocol tasks,
while the head of government should carry out functional duties.
</P>
<P>
Wahid's idea has met with opposition from critics who say the
proposal is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
Chief of TNI territorial affairs Lt. Gen. Susilo Bambang
Yudhoyono said the military was seeking alternatives to avoid a
possible deadlock in the presidential election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
