<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Spokeswoman Refutes Japanese Official's Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Ministry
Spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue today strongly refuted a Japanese official
's remarks concerning the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular news conference here, Zhang said that any
attempt to incorporate Taiwan into the scope of Japan-U.S.
security cooperation constitutes a serious infringement upon China
's sovereignty and a gross interference in China's internal
affairs, and is unacceptable to and will be firmly opposed by the
Chinese government and people.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said this when asked to comment on the June 23 remarks
made by Taku Yamazaki, a Japanese parliamentarian from the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party and chairman of the Special Committee of
Japan-U.S. Defense Cooperation Guidelines of Japan's House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
Yamazaki said that Japan would surely provide support to the
United States if China liberates Taiwan by force, which he
believes will "bring about major influence on the peace and
security of Japan."
</P>
<P>
"We are surprised by and indignant at the remarks made by an
important official of Japan's ruling party to interfere in China's
internal affairs," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
As is known to all, Taiwan is an inalienable part of China's
territory and the Taiwan issue is purely China's internal affair,
Zhang added.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government has made clear-cut commitment and
statement to this effect in the Sino-Japanese Joint Statement, the
spokeswoman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
