<HEADLINE> U.S. to Compensate Kenya Businesses for Bomb Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government has set aside
four million U.S. dollars for compensation to the Kenyan
small-scale businesses that incurred losses during the 1998
August bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Finance Minister Francis Masakhalia told Parliament that
his government was awaiting an assessment report on the losses
incurred by the businesses during the tragedy before considering
the amount of money to compensate them, the state-run Kenya Times
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report would be finalized by July 2 of this year,
Masakhalia added.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. government had committed 37 million dollars
toward compensation of last year's August bomb blast victims and
that 11 million dollars had been released and disbursed.
</P>
<P>
Masakhalia noted that the compensation by the U.S. would cover
medical, business losses and other expenses incurred by Kenyans
during the tragedy. 
</P>
