<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam, Thailand to Boost Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam and Thailand discussed
concrete measures to boost bilateral economic cooperation during
the sixth session of the Vietnam-Thailand Joint Commission on
Economic Cooperation here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Minister of Planning and Investment Tran Xuan Gia was
quoted by local press as saying that the two sides reached an
agreement in preparation for a liquefied petroleum gas bottling
project in Danang. An appropriate site is being sought.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese minister announced that the Bangkok-Danang air
route would be opened on October 31.
</P>
<P>
The two sides, Gia said, discussed the possibility that Vietnam
would export its crude oil to Thailand and would first send crude
sample for Thailand's evaluation.
</P>
<P>
Gia and Thai Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan have signed a
memorandum of understanding on the session, which focused on
commerce, investment, technology, communications, transport,
fisheries cooperation, energy and oil.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade between Vietnam and Thailand last year amounted
to 969 million U.S. dollars, a rise of 27 percent from 1997. There
are 90 Thai projects operating in Vietnam with a combined capital
of about 1.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam and Thailand have recently signed a pact on joint naval
patrols in the adjoining waters and on establishing a continuous
information exchange network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
