<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cracks Down on Imports of Soft-Shelled Turtle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Agriculture is
to reinforce the ban on the illegal importing of soft-shelled
turtles to protect domestic turtle resources and the interests of
turtle breeders in the country.
</P>
<P>
An official from the ministry's fishery department said today
that in recent years, huge quantities of soft-shelled turtles have
been imported illegally to China, which once mixed with fine
domestic turtle strains have resulted in a downgrading of domestic
turtle resources.
</P>
<P>
"Turtles entering the country without quarantine also brought
in new diseases," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also blamed the dumping of imported turtles for impacting on
the production and sales of soft-shelled turtles in China.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that some 20,000 to 30,000 such turtles are
brought into China through various channels every year, most from
Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The breeding of turtles has been a backbone of China's aquatic
industry. In 1998, the output of soft-shelled turtles reached 60,
000 tons, worth an estimated four billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
