<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Suffers Heavy Economic Loss by NATO Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia has suffered an
economic loss of 29.6 billion U.S. dollars by three months of NATO
bombing starting March 24.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary figure does not include damages to military
facilities and equipment, natural resources and ecological
environment, Mladjan Dinkic, author of a new book, said at a press
conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Dinkic said his book was based on reliable information from
government agencies and media reports and on-the-spot
investigations. He said his country urgently needed 1.1 billion
dollars of aid from the international community to settle refugees,
restore power grid, rebuild damaged residential houses and bridges,
solve the problem of unemployment and provide social protection.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Dinkic said, Yugoslavia will need 3 billion
dollars in direct investment from abroad every year in the coming
five years to maintain a steady and sustained economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
