<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans To Halt Decline of Postal Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 24 (Xinhua) -- A major campaign is to be
launched by China's postal authorities to try and reverse the
sectors devastating financial deficits over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Liu Liqing, director of the State Post Bureau, made the vow at
a national conference recently held here focused on improving the
postal service which lost a staggering 14 billion yuan (1.7
billion U.S. dollars) last year because of strong market
competition and rival modern communications technology.
</P>
<P>
He said that the bureau has decided to introduce new services,
including mail for commercial purposes and post cards carrying
paid advertising, to meet customers' demands and halt the decline.
</P>
<P>
Liu also suggested that post offices operate as agents for
insurance companies and banks, and that the sector should
strengthen its internal financial management and speed up the
introduction of a computer network.
</P>
<P>
The postal sector has long been the backbone of China's
communications system, and at times it was the only information
bridge connecting cities with distant villages across vast areas
of land.
</P>
<P>
But the rapid development of the telephone and even E-mail
services in the 1990s has almost left it standing, resulting in
rocketing deficits and a mounting number of laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
The change in fortunes was also influenced by the separation of
the postal sector from the former Posts and Telecommunications
Ministry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Moves to Increase Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen, China's first special
economic zone, has adopted a number of measures to increase
exports.
</P>
<P>
The city in Guangdong Province has slashed inspection fees by
an average 30 percent for both export commodities manufactured
with supplied materials and imported materials.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen has also reduced fees for evaluating equipment and
other commodities imported by foreign-funded enterprises by as
much as 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
The city's general trade import volume for the first three
months hit 1.13 billion US dollars, up 1.2-fold on the previous
year's period. Total exports for the period stood at 5.57 billion
US dollars. Shenzhen attracted foreign investments totaling 514
million US dollars, up 7.7 percent on an annual basis. 
</P>
