<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 08:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Moves to Scuttle UN Conference on Settlements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Israel is being engaged in
intensive diplomatic efforts to scuttle a U.N.-sponsored
international conference expected to condemn Israel for its
settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
The conference, set for July 15 in Geneva, was decided upon by
a special session of the General Assembly last year at the
initiative of the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) after the
outgoing Likud government decided to build settlements at a
controversial site outside Arab East Jerusalem, the Haaretz daily
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The conference is scheduled to discuss means to enforce
application of the Fourth Geneva Convention, which deals with
treatment of civilians in occupied territories. All signatory
countries were invited.
</P>
<P>
Israel has claimed that the Geneva Convention is not
applicable in Gaza, West Bank and East Jerusalem, which it seized
from the hands of Arab states in the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
But a preparatory meeting for the Geneva conference held in
Cairo last week at UN initiative concluded with a resolution
stating that the Geneva Convention does apply to these areas.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also criticized Israel for violating human
rights of the Palestinians and destroying "the social and
economic infrastructure" in these territories.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians see the building of Jewish settlements in these
territories as illegal and violation of signed agreements
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Foreign Ministry said the cancellation of the
Geneva conference will be considered a good will gesture toward
the incoming Israeli government of Ehud Barak, the Labor leader
who defeated hard-line Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in the
May elections.
</P>
<P>
Barak, a moderate ex-army chief, has pledged to move
forward the Middle East peace process largely frozen in the
three years of Netanyahu's office.
</P>
<P>
Barak has until July 9 to put together a coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Israel's efforts to block the conference are focused on two
channels: asking Western countries to boycott the meeting and
recruiting international support to pressure the PNA to abandon
its initiative, Haaretz said.
</P>
<P>
The paper said there is disagreement within the PNA as to
whether to go ahead with the conference in the wake of the new
political situation in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Canada and Australia have said they will
boycott the gathering, the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Gold Output Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Gold output in China totaled 56.6
tons during the January-May period this year, decreasing by 2.4
tons or 4.1 percent over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from the State Gold Administration, the
figure accounts for 32.3 percent of the planned output of this
year.
</P>
<P>
China is planning to produce 175 tons of gold this year, with
gold enterprises reaping total profits of one billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Monthly gold output increased markedly over the previous months
to 13.22 tons in May, though the figure was lower than in the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
An official from the administration attributed the decrease of
gold output to the shutdown of many small gold mines, which lack
competitiveness as gold prices kept fluctuating at lower levels.
</P>
<P>
He said that further restructuring of the gold industry and the
government's efforts to slow down the output growth were also
factors for the drop in gold output.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China, the country's central bank, lowered
the purchasing price of gold consecutively on May 20 and June 9,
cutting it by 11.95 percent. The move has had a good impact on the
country's gold industry.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the year, gold enterprises have
painstakingly secured a rapid increase of profits by cutting costs
and improving proficiency.
</P>
<P>
China produced 172.8 tons of gold last year, when gold
enterprises earned total profits of one billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
