<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism Declared New Zealand's Biggest Export Earner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Tourism has been officially
announced to be New Zealand's biggest export earner.
</P>
<P>
According to the Tourism Satellite Account, the first official
measurement of tourism's impact on the economy issued by the New
Zealand Government Statistician and circulated here Thursday, New
Zealand's international visitors spent 4.3 billion NZ dollars
(2.4 billion U.S. dollars) on goods and services in 1995.
</P>
<P>
This represented a nearly 16 percent contribution to the total
exports of the country, putting tourism a nose ahead of aluminium
and raw material exports such as iron, wool, fats and oils, and a
neck in front of dairy products and manufactured goods.
</P>
<P>
Statistics New Zealand said tourism's earnings have been rising
since then.
</P>
<P>
The pilot account showed tourism in 1995 provided full-time
jobs for 58,000 people and another 60,000 people were employed
indirectly in supporting the sector.
</P>
<P>
Tourism directly contributed 2.9 billion NZ dollars (1.6
billion U.S. dollars) or 3.4 percent to the country's gross
domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
According to the New Zealand official statistical organ,
agriculture was the biggest contributor at nearly six percent.
</P>
<P>
Total spending in New Zealand by all tourists was 9.1 billion
NZ dollars (5 billion U.S. dollars) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Of this 4.3 billion NZ dollars (2.4 billion U.S. dollars) were
spent by overseas visitors, and 3.5 billion NZ dollars (1.9
billion U.S. dollars) by New Zealand households traveling for
recreation and pleasure, while the remaining 1.3 billion NZ
dollars (700 million U.S. dollars) were spent on travel by
business and government.
</P>
<P>
The 4.3 billion NZ dollars spent by international visitors to
New Zealand accounted for 15.8 percent of total export earnings
for 1995, more than any other export category. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
