<HEADLINE> Landlocked Chinese Province Attracting More Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG June 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 30,000 overseas tourists
and 3.45 million Chinese have visited Guizhou Province in southern
China in the first five months of this year, up 9.3 percent and 58.
4 percent respectively from the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou has the fifth largest number of ethnic minority people
in China. It has opened up 120 scenic spots, eight of which are at
the state level. It also has 240 cultural relic sites and 24 areas
with ethnic minority villages.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, the provincial government has made tourism as a
pillar industry and has spent heavily on improving infrastructure,
building Longdongbao Airport and highways from Guiyang, the
provincial capital, to Huangguoshu Waterfalls and to the city of
Zunyi.
</P>
<P>
It has also set up 40 hotels and restaurants and 82 travel
services and a large number of entertainment facilities in the
past few years and has more than 50,000 people working in the
tourism business.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, more than 20 million domestic and overseas tourists
visited Guizhou. This is in contrast to only 2 million in the
1980s. Tourism revenues reached nearly 4 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
This year, the number of tourists is expected to increase 20
percent over last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
