<HEADLINE> U.S. Amway Shows Good Performance in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. direct-sales company Amway
(China) had an average of 67 percent growth in sales in the April-
May period over March, China Economic Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The company source says that the increased sales are the
result of the company's first obvious price cut since it opened in
China in 1995, a cut of from 30 to 40 percent on 23 of Amway's
daily-use products.
</P>
<P>
Lower tariffs on dozens of imported materials made the price
cut possible, according to the company, which says that other
factors include a fall in the tax rate on some luxury items as
well as improved efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Amway has decided to hold a big show of its products in
Beijing at the end of this month, the paper reports.
</P>
<P>
Amway is the largest direct-sales company in the world. It has
increased investment and efforts to explore the Chinese market in
spite of the fact that China has banned certain aspect of direct
sales service.  
</P>
</TEXT>
