<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Shilling Gains Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan shilling extended its
winning streak against the U.S. dollar Wednesday with the improved
dollar inflow from agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Kenya (CBK) Wednesday posted the shilling
at a mean commercial rate of 73.46 to the dollar from 74.36
Monday, while commercial banks quoted the shilling at 73.10/73.30
to the dollar from 73. 30/73.60 at Monday's close, the East
African Standard reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Local dealers said demand for dollars was subdued while inflows
from tea and coffee sales had improved, easing fears of a
prolonged dollar shortage.
</P>
<P>
The Coffee Board of Kenya said Monday that deliveries for
parchment increased to 60,759 tons since the beginning of 1998/99
crop year compared to 39,065 tons in the 1997/98 period.
</P>
<P>
Vikram Samsi, head of treasury at the Standard Chartered Bank,
said he expected the exchange rate to settle at 68 to 70 shillings
to the dollar in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
The shilling has clawed back against the dollar in the past
three days, helped by a surge in interested rates on treasury
bills that is expected to lure foreign exchange to the money
market.
</P>
<P>
Against the pound and euro, the central bank quoted the
shilling at a mean indicative rate of 116.85 and 75.98
respectively from 117.97 and 76.61 at Monday's open. 
</P>
</TEXT>
