<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spurs Beat Knicks 96-89 in NBA Finals Game 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 23 (Xinhua) -- David Robinson grabbed control of
the NBA Finals and would not let go.
</P>
<P>
Robinson's clutch scoring, rebounding and shot-blocking gave
the San Antonio Spurs a 96-89 victory over the New York Knicks and
a stranglehold on the series here tonight.
</P>
<P>
Waiting 10 years for a championship, Robinson displayed his
veteran leadership with 14 points, 17 rebounds and four blocks. He
had a response for every fourth-quarter push by the Knicks, who
went cold down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
"David was just a monster," Spurs coach Gregg Popovich said. "I
'm so happy for him because he showed a lot of people what he
could do. A lot of people counted him out this year for reasons
that I'm still trying to figure out. But he was absolutely awesome.
"
</P>
<P>
With Tim Duncan laboring through another erratic fourth quarter
and the Knicks rallying, Robinson took control on both backboards.
"Big Dave stepped up with some great defensive plays," Spurs guard
Jaren Jackson said. "He played a big-time game. He was our best
player on the floor."
</P>
<P>
San Antonio grabbed 49 rebounds to 34 for New York, which
seemed to submit to San Antonio's size.
</P>
<P>
Duncan had 28 points and 18 rebounds for the Spurs, who have a
3-1 lead in the best-of-seven series and can win their first NBA
title on Friday in New York. No team has rallied from a 3-1
deficit in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
"Size does matter in this league," Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy
said. "It does, and particularly in the playoffs."
</P>
<P>
San Antonio bounced back from a Game 3 loss and improved to 14-
2 in the playoffs, having not lost consecutive games since
February 28.
</P>
<P>
Latrell Sprewell scored 26 points and Allan Houston added 20
for the Knicks, who missed eight straight shots down the stretch,
sending the rabid Madison Square Garden crowd scurrying for the
exits.
</P>
<P>
"We didn't execute well down the stretch with about two minutes
to go," Sprewell said. "We were stuck on 84 for what seemed like
the longest time."
</P>
<P>
Marcus Camby started at center for the second straight game and
had 20 points and 13 rebounds. But he had no answer for Robinson,
who hammered him inside.
</P>
<P>
The next game will start on Friday here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
