<HEADLINE> Hezbollah, SLA in Secret Talks Over Prisoner Swap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Secret negotiations are under way
to arrange a new swap of four pro-Israeli militiamen held by
Lebanese guerrilla group Hezbollah for its fighters held in the
militia's prison, the Daily Star reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The swap is being mediated by the International Committee
for the Red Cross (ICRC), which has been allowed to visit the four
South Lebanon Army (SLA) militiamen being detained by Hezbollah,
the paper quoted Parliament member Mohammed Raad, who heads the
group's politburo, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The four detainees, who are all from Jezzine, southern Lebanese
region which has been recently evacuated by SLA after a 14-year
occupation, were captured at different times this year while
performing their duties in the Israeli occupied border zone in
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
The 2,500-strong militia was trained and armed by Israel to
help it patrol the border zone and police Jezzine, just north of
the zone.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, is leading a
guerrilla war trying to oust Israeli forces and its proxy SLA out
of the country.
</P>
<P>
It is still unknown about the number of detainees the group
hoped to free from the Khiam Detention Center in south Lebanon in
exchange for the four SLA men. Approximately 150 Lebanese are
reportedly being held in the SLA-run prison.
</P>
<P>
In June 1998, Israel exchanged 65 Lebanese detainees and the
remains of 40 resistance fighters for the remains of one Israeli
soldier.
</P>
<P>
The swap was conducted through former Lebanese government of
Rafik Hariri, French government and ICRC.
</P>
<P>
In July 1996, Hezbollah and Israel exchanged the remains of two
Israeli soldiers held by the group since 1986 for the bodies of
123 resistance fighters under a German-brokered deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
