<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands of Zambian Babies Born with HIV: UNICEF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Zambian babies are
born infected with the Human Immuno Virus (HIV) that causes the
deadly Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS), United Nations
Children's Fund (UNCEF) disclosed.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF representative Peter McDermott said Wednesday these
children have a five-to-six year life expectancy, thus creating
more social problems for a developing country like Zambia.
</P>
<P>
This puts the country among the world's worst affected in this
regard, McDermott said, while addressing a Mother To Child
Transmission (MTCT) of HIV Initiative here.
</P>
<P>
If not checked, the problem would eat up the nation's political
and socio-economic fabric, Zambian newspaper, The Post, Thursday
quoted McDermott as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We should not under-estimate what this problem can do to a
country. Unless something serious is done, urgently, HIV/AIDS will
affect the country in all spheres of life," he said.
</P>
<P>
Africa and other developing countries should not feel
discouraged from fighting the disease because of its scarce
financial resources, McDermott said.
</P>
<P>
Citing polio as an example of a disease not contained in most
countries, McDemott said the same determination used in
vanquishing the disease should be employed in overcoming AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"People thought Africa could not control polio because of its
scarce resources but with zeal the Third World countries have
proved the world wrong. Even AIDS can be controlled if we unite
and put all we have in the fight against this problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It's expensive, there are no resources, people will say. But
Zambia is an excellent example of how polio has been contained
despite the earlier pessimism when the campaign started," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, MTCT-HIV coordinating team member Chewe Luo said
three sites have been opened countrywide to identify HIV positive
expectant mothers so they can be injected with an anti-AIDS
vaccine to prevent transmission of the disease on to their babies.
</P>
<P>
"We will start with 10,000 expectant mothers and then reduce to
3,000 whom we'll use as sample for this project," she said,
adding: about 400,000 U.S. dollars will be used to implement this
project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
