<HEADLINE> Nigerian Senate Passes 42 of President's 49 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Senate Wednesday passed 42
of President Olusegun Obasanjo's 49 ministerial nominees,
concluding the marathon clearance only days before its expiration.
</P>
<P>
The list to be announced by the president will form Nigeria's
first civilian government for years.
</P>
<P>
Seven candidates were deleted from the list, which was not yet
published, because the sites of their origin have already secured
enough representation in the government, according to the Senate
sources.
</P>
<P>
"we will communicate our final decision to the president, who
will thereafter make it public along with the portfolios," said
Senator Joseph Waku after the ending of Wednesday's session of the
upper house of Nigeria' s National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The clearance of the list was delayed when the senators were
asking for more personal information on the ministerial nominees
last week.
</P>
<P>
The clearance was also proceeded amid severe quarrels between
the majority People's Democratic Party (PDP), and the two minority
parties the Alliance for Democracy (AD) and All People's Party
(APP).
</P>
<P>
The AD and APP senators Tuesday walked out of the National
Assembly Building to protest a corruption accusation against
them, leaving the PDP senators continuing their debate alone in
the building.
</P>
<P>
The protest took place when an AD sponsored motion seeking to
census PDP Senator Gbenga Aluko was killed. The motion demand a
apology from Aluku for allegedly designating the image of the AD
and APP senators in a newspaper pronouncement charging their
senators with involving in bribery and corruption.
</P>
<P>
President Obasanjo has been lobbying for a quickened step of
the Senator when the delay has put off many key policy decisions.
</P>
