<HEADLINE> World Bank Loan Helping Compulsory Education On Chinese Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, June 24 (Xinhua) -- a 5-million-U.S.-dollar project of
World Bank loans for introducing compulsory education to 6
impoverished counties in China's island province of Hainan has
just received official approval.
</P>
<P>
It is a part of a WB loan package worth 70 million U.S. dollars
that began in 1997. It is the fourth program to increase the 9-
year compulsory education system in impoverished parts of Hainan,
Heilongjiang, and Yunnan provinces. The whole project is expected
to be completed by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
Work on 127 schools with 40,000 sq.m of floor space has been
completed in Hainan with the loan money and local funds. Another
60 schools are still under construction. More than 5,000 students
from poor families are expected to get financial aid from the
loans to complete their schooling. 
</P>
