<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Community Health Program In Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- For Tibetans living alongside 8,848-
meter Qomolungma, the highest peak in the Himalayas, one of the
most popular figure is Zhenqiong, who has helped villagers heal
diseases and plant trees.
</P>
<P>
Zhenqiong is a 'Pendeba', a Tibetan word for welfare worker.
He is responsible for healthcare in villages. In 1994, with help
from the U.S.'s New Generation Fund, the Pendeba International
Assistance Project was begun by the Qomolungma Peak Nature Reserve
in the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The Pendebas provide medical services and environmental
protection information and help villagers increase their income,
according to the project manager, Zhuoma. The program has been an
effective way to make better use of villagers' ability to deal
with health problem and environmental and economic issues, she
says.
</P>
<P>
There are currently 224 Pendebas working in 80 percent of the
local villages who are mainly responsible for government
immunization and family planning programs.
</P>
<P>
In some villages, they have helped set up a special fund, the
Villagers Welfare Society Fund, to make up for fund shortages of
public health institutions in villages and townships.
</P>
<P>
The Pendebas have also made traditional Tibetan medicines from
medicinal herb that are favored by the villagers and foreign
tourists as well.
</P>
<P>
The five-year old Pendeba program has helped bring down the
infant death rate 50 percent, Zhuoma says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
