<HEADLINE> China Renovating Largest Mosque In North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The largest mosque in Hohhot in
China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region is showing its grandeur
again after a year of renovation.
</P>
<P>
The 2-million-yuan (240,000 U.S. dollars) project which was
paid for by Muslim donations and the local government began on
July 1, 1998. It included some expansion of the original arch and
reception hall in an area exceeding 1,000 sq.m.
</P>
<P>
The mosque was built in 1693 during the Qing Dynasty and has
had several repairs since then. The total area used to be as large
as 4,000 sq.m. and had a gate, hall, washroom, and lecture room.
</P>
<P>
This large mosque is the oldest and best-kept mosque of its
kind in the region and contains 30 volumes of the Koran and dozens
of ancient steles. 
</P>
