<HEADLINE> Pine Trees Dying in Scenic Spot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Pine trees in the Laoshan Mountains,
a famous scenic spot in the coastal city of Qingdao in east China'
s Shandong province, are dying of branch-rot, a disease local
experts have no way to eradicate.
</P>
<P>
The disease first showed up in May and has so far caused the
death of more than 400 hectares of the 2,133 hectares of pine
trees in Laoshan, with another 266 hectares being affected.
</P>
<P>
Located half an hour's drive from the city proper of Qingdao,
renowned for its top-brand beer, the Laoshan mountain attracts
many tourists from both home and abroad with its grotesque view
and pine-tree forests.
</P>
<P>
Local workers are now cutting down the dead trees to save the
rest, under instruction from a number of experts.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Kegong, professor with the Nanjing Forestry University,
said the only efficient way to prevent further spread of the
disease is to fell and burn all sick trees.
</P>
<P>
"More efficient means are yet to be sought," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
According to Hu Zexu, director of the Laoshan Forest Farm, the
pine variety in Laoshan was introduced from Japan in the 1950s.
</P>
</TEXT>
