<HEADLINE> Flood Hits Southeastern Bangladeshi Districts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- At least 400,000 people have been
marooned in water and about 250,000 acres of land with standing
crops and housing have gone under water in Southeast Bangladesh's
Chittagong District, The Bangladesh Observer reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains over the past several days caused flash flood
in Chittagong and Cox's Bazar, another southeastern district,
killing two persons in Chittagong and one in Cox's Bazar.
</P>
<P>
All the 25 thanas (sub-districts) of Chittagong District were
more or less affected and the divisional headquarters, the seaport
city of Chittagong, remained cut off from some thana headquarters
of the district by road for the past two days.
</P>
<P>
Chittagong was also cut off from the three southeastern hill
districts -- Rangamati, Khagrachhari and Bandarban -- by road
traffic on Wednesday, as a considerable part of roads connecting
these districts went under water.
</P>
<P>
The Arakan road linking Chittagong and the sea resort town of
Cox's Bazar was inundated at several points. The water level in
the Halda River, one of the major rivers in the region, already
crossed the danger mark, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
