<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Parliament Begins Debate on Budget Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's House of
Representatives Thursday began debating on the budget bill for
fiscal 2000, which starts on October 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai briefed the legislators on the
budget, which is worth 860 billion baht (23.2 billion U.S.
dollars), or 16 percent of the country's 5.42 trillion baht (146.4
billion dollars) gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The budget, a 4.2-percent increase from the previous fiscal
year, carries a 110-billion-baht (2.97 billion dollars) deficit,
or 2.2 percent of the GDP, based on the government's capability to
generate a revenue of only 750 billion baht (20.2 billion dollars)
from tax collection.
</P>
<P>
A deficit budget showed the government's resolution to
stimulate the economy by government expenditure at a time when
private consumption is weak.
</P>
<P>
The budget allocations are aimed largely at toning down the
adverse effects of the crisis on the social front, improving the
state administrative system, increasing the potential of manpower
and society for sustainable development and restructuring the
economy and economic infrastructure to speed up recovery.
</P>
<P>
The debate is expected to last three days till Saturday, when
legislators will vote on the budget bill.
</P>
<P>
Despite the opposition's allegation that the budget is
relatively too small to really kick-start the economic recovery,
the ruling coalition, with Prime Minister Chuan's Democrat Party
at its core, is confident to win enough "yes" votes.
</P>
<P>
The six-party coalition holds a 257 majority in the 393-strong
lower house. 
</P>
</TEXT>
