<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Thais Unsure of Recovery This Year: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Despite the government's
confidence, most Thai people are still not sure that Thailand's
economic recovery will take place in the second half of this year,
said a poll conducted by a leading research center.
</P>
<P>
Some 82.9 percent of the polled respondents were not convinced
by the government's remedial measures due to some unsolved
problems, especially rising unemployment, slower export growth and
the increasing non-performing loans, Thai Farmers Research Center
said in a report which was available Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The poll, entitled "Will the Economy Recover in 1999?", is a
qualitative survey, collecting data from 4,833 samples nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Only 17.1 percent of the respondents were certain that the
economy would recover, claiming the government had tried every
possible way to handle the problems.
</P>
<P>
As for the impact on their daily life, 47.4 percent of those
surveyed said they had cut consumption expenditure, especially for
utilities, such as furniture, electrical appliances, mobile phones
and pagers.
</P>
<P>
They had also sharply cut spending at leisure spots, on dining
out and nightlife.
</P>
<P>
The economic recession has led to adjustments in business
operation. 58.6 percent of the respondents have stopped business
expansion, but 16.7 percent still see promising opportunities in
agri-business and daily-life business.
</P>
<P>
Most of the polled respondents also disclosed that business
adjustments for survival is now their top priority. Emphasis will
be given to efficient personnel management.
</P>
<P>
With regard to government performance, the polled entrepreneurs
voiced the opinion that the government had shown strong intentions
to fully remedy the economic problems. But the problems are too
complex to overcome in a short period of time.
</P>
<P>
Of the total samples, 51.5 percent are in Greater Bangkok, 11.3
percent in the northeast, 10.3 percent in the east, 9.5 percent in
the north, 8.9 percent in the central and 8.5 percent in the
south.
</P>
<P>
By occupation, 21.1 percent of the respondents run their own
businesses while 17.9 percent are employees of private
enterprises, 15.9 percent housewives, 15.6 percent hired workers,
15 percent government officials, 6.8 percent state employees and
7.7 percent others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
