<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Passes Austerity Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The German government Wednesday
passed an austerity plan to cut 30 billion marks (16 billion U.S.
dollars) in federal budget next year.
</P>
<P>
 The austerity plan is part of the reform package which was
described by Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder as the "biggest (
economic) reform project that postwar Germany has ever seen."
</P>
<P>
 Under the package, initiated by Finance Minister Hans Eichel
with Labor Minister Walter Riester's help in the reform of the
social security system, Germany is to curb 8 billion marks (4.2
billion dollars) of corporate tax from the year 2001 in a bid to
sharpen the competitive edge of the country's business sector.
</P>
<P>
The government will start next January to raise its subsidiary
for children while slightly lowering pensions for the old and the
jobless.
</P>
<P>
Labor unions, who have strong influence in Schroeder's party,
swiftly criticized package as unfairly harsh on pensioners and the
jobless.
</P>
<P>
German industry welcomed the measures, but complained that the
corporate tax relief should be brought forward from 2001.
</P>
<P>
According to the plans, Germany will continue its ecological
reforms by increasing the price of gasoline by 6.0 percent of a
mark per liter every year in the four years to come to help
finance cuts in social security contributions by workers and
employers, which drive up German labor costs.
</P>
<P>
At the same time the price of power will rise at the rate of 0.
5 percent of a mark each year.
</P>
<P>
Parliament is expected to vote on the package in the fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
