<HEADLINE> U.S. to Send Troop Reinforcements to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Despite the end of NATO airstrikes
against Yugoslavia, the United States will send more troops to
Albania to strengthen the U.S. military presence in the Balkan
region, the Albanian Telegraphic Agency said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Reinforcements will arrive under a White House order, the
report quoted a spokesman for the U.S. task force in Albania as
saying. He did not say when and how many troops will come, but
made it clear that they will be deployed in different places.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. task force in Albania is mainly composed of Marine
Corps equipped with heavy weapons including the Apache attack
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
After Belgrade withdrew all its forces from Kosovo on June 20,
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana announced the official end to
the alliance's bombardment of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Now, British, French, German, Italian and other NATO member
states' troops are leaving Albania for Kosovo to take part in the
peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
However, a senior NATO military official told Albanian Prime
Minister Pandeli Majko on Wednesday that NATO troops will not
leave Albania until all of NATO's objectives have been achieved.
</P>
</TEXT>
