<HEADLINE> City Square Becomes New Symbol Of Tibetan Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- It's a normal day on Potala Palace
Square in Lhasa, the capital of the Tibet Autonomous Region, but
the square is something special for local people, and a young baby
struggles toward pigeons that are being fed by tourists while a
group of soldiers take pictures with Potala Palace as a backdrop.
</P>
<P>
Sangji, the 73-year-old grandmother of the baby, says she
suffers from leg problems but still often comes to the square in
front of Potala Palace. The elderly woman lives in Bharkor Street,
the old part of Lhasa, and explains that the square used to be a
garbage dump in the suburbs of Lhasa,.
</P>
<P>
At one corner, seven-year-old Suoqiong is playing with a toy
locomotive, but he's probably too young to know that Tibet is the
only province-level administrative region in China that has no
railways. Work on the Qinghai-Tibet Railway was halted in Golmud
in Qinghai because of many obstacles.
</P>
<P>
On the other side of the square, a silver-colored air fighter
is attracting a large number of herdsmen. The Chinese Air Force
presented the retired aircraft to Tibetan children in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Potala Palace Square was built from a smaller square, Cultural
Square, in 1995, with 110 million yuan from the central government,
says Ngawang Ngamgyai, administrator in charge of the square. It
covers 240,000 square meters and is the second largest in China
after Tian'anmen in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Loud speakers and a large water fountain and pool occupy the
center of the square, which has ballrooms, a library, a playground,
shops, an outdoor market, and a pond for boating around it. A 100-
member cleaning team is at work on the square, which costs more
than 2 million yuan a year to maintain. Their worst fear is of
windstorms that could destroy the equipment, especially the
expensive lights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
