<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Timor Ballot Delay Accepted by Rival Factions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- East Timor rival factions welcomed
and accepted the U.N. decision to delay by two weeks the August 8
ballot on the future of the territory, The Indonesian Observer
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan decided on Tuesday to
postpone the crucial vote on self-determination of the former
Portuguese colony.
</P>
<P>
In a six-page report to the U.N. Security Council, Annan did
not give a precise date. But U.N. officials said they expected the
poll to take place either on August 21 or August 22.
</P>
<P>
Pro-integration organizations in East Timor said they would
benefit from the delay in the direct ballot on self-rule for the
territory.
</P>
<P>
The organizations "will give a positive contribution to the
United Nations to create a conducive, stable and peaceful
situation for the ballot," Lopes da Cruz, leader of the
newly-formed United Front for East Timor Autonomy, said.
</P>
<P>
Da Cruz is also the Indonesian government's envoy with special
responsibility for East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Another pro-integration leader, Basilio Araujo, welcomed
Annan's decision. "For us it is no problem. It will give us more
time to prepare."
</P>
<P>
Jailed East Timorese pro-independence leader Jose Alexandre
"Xanana" Gusmao said he backed the U.N. decision to delay the
vote.
</P>
<P>
"All parties involved in this process, and obviously the U.N.
secretary general, are unanimous in considering that the existence
of conditions of security and tranquillity in East Timor is a
prerequisite and a sine qua non condition for the holding of a
free, fair and democratic consultation," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated his commitment "to continuing to work and
cooperate with all parties involved in the self-determination
process so as to guarantee to the people of East Timor the needed
and yearned-for peace and tranquillity."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Foreign Affairs Minister Ali Alatas said Indonesia
accepts the postponement of the direct ballot in East Timor, but
rejects security as the reason behind the delay.
</P>
<P>
Annan said in his report that pro-integration militias in East
Timor were intimidating voters in rural areas, "thus jeopardizing
the necessary openness of the consultation (voting) process."
</P>
<P>
Alatas said he hoped the decision was made for fair and honest
reasons.
</P>
<P>
"In Indonesia's view, concerning a delay with security
conditions as a pretext, we regard it as unfair," he said after
meeting with President B.J. Habibie and other ministers here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said the delay was probably caused by logistics hurdles,
saying the U.N. Security Council was late in its approval of the
U.N. Mission in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister/Armed Forces Chief Gen. Wiranto also pointed
out that the security in East Timor should not be made the
scapegoat for the postponement of the ballot in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the June 7 general election in East Timor was
peaceful, proof that security is conducive to the ballots.
</P>
<P>
The August ballot in East Timor will allow the territory's
people to choose whether their homeland should become an
autonomous region within Indonesia or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
East Timor was integrated into Indonesia in 1976 in a move
never recognized by the United Nations, which still considers
Portugal as the administering power of the territory.
</P>
<P>
Early this year Indonesia announced it would grant East Timor
independence if the people in the territory reject Indonesia's
offer of wide-ranging autonomy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
