<HEADLINE> S. Korean Company to Build Apartments in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 24 (Xinhua) -- A South Korean construction
company is to build 10,000 apartments for the relocation of
low-income families in the capital city of Colombo, the Sri Lankan
Ministry of Housing and Urban Development said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It is a part of the commitment of the ministry toward upgrading
the living standards of about 60,000 families in the slum areas of
the city, a ministry spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"We will also appoint a standing committee to monitor the
progress of the project," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Chairman J.T. Nam of Wooree Seohee Construction (Pvt.) Ltd.
said they were prepared to invest 350 million rupees (5 million
U.S. dollars) initially to build the 10,000 apartments and work
will commence within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
He said his company had vast experience in constructing
pre-fabricated housing for various income categories over the past
10 years.
</P>
<P>
The construction system comprises a mild steel structural frame
and a light weight wall, roof panels, concrete floors and aluminum
doors.
</P>
<P>
A factory to produce low-cost building materials will also be
constructed.
</P>
<P>
Once the construction work here is completed, the company hoped
to move to the plantation and rural areas with bigger investment,
Nam said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
