<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Myanmar Takes Measures to Eradicate Drugs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Strengthening of international and bilateral cooperation also
constitutes one of Myanmar's measures in fighting drugs. Myanmar
became a state party to the 1961 Single Convention on Narcotic
Drugs in July 1963 and is also a signatory to the 1988 Convention
Against Trafficking in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances
and 1971 Convention on the substances.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Drug Control Program (UNDCP) has extended a total of
15 million U.S. dollars of aid to Myanmar for the implementation
of a five-year drug eradication project (1998-2003) in the Wa
region, the country's northern Shan state.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has also joined a six-nation memorandum of
understanding on sub-regional cooperation in drug abuse control
involving the UNDCP. These six nations are China, Cambodia, Laos,
Myanmar, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Myanmar reached bilateral cooperation agreements to
control illicit drug trafficking and abuse with India in 1993,
with Bangladesh in 1994, with Vietnam in 1995 and with the Russian
Federation, Laos and the Philippines in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The country also carried out four joint poppy-yield surveys in
Shan state with the United States in 1993, 1995, 1997 and 1998
under the two countries' anti-drug program. One more survey is
planned in 1999.
</P>
<P>
As one of Myanmar's drug eradication efforts, it steps up
dissemination of information and education against the serious
danger of drug, calling on people to keep away from drugs.
</P>
<P>
The country is also building two drug museums, while carrying
out education on prevention against drugs for its citizens,
especially young students, through radio, television, newspapers,
magazines, movies, video, exhibitions and seminars. These efforts
have made achievements to certain extent.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has also established drug treatment centers throughout
the country, providing compulsory treatment of addicts. So far,
six major centers of this kind have been set up in Yangon,
Mandalay, Myitkyina and Taunggyi, admitting 2,000 addicts
annually.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, there were 66,463 registered
drug addicts in the country, of whom 50.01 percent deal with
opium, 37.4 percent with heroin, 7.7 percent with tranquilizer and
4.89 percent with other drugs.
</P>
<P>
According to officially published figures, during the past 10
years between 1988 and 1998, Myanmar seized a total of 4,125 kilos
of heroin, 28,385.89 kilos of opium, 6,606 kilos of marijuana and
26.96 million tablets of amphetamine stimulants.
</P>
<P>
During the period, 32,787 hectares of poppy plantations were
destroyed, resulting in a drop of 356.17 tons of opium production.
The country's Mongla region in eastern Shan state was declared as
"drug-free zone" in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has started in 1999 implementing a plan, aimed at total
eradication of drugs in the whole country in 15 years. The plan is
estimated to cost 5.6 billion dollars and will be carried out in
three phases -- the first phase is from fiscal 1999-2000 to
2003-2004, the second one from 2004-2005 to 2008-2009 and the
third one from 2009-2010 to 2013-2014. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.K. Secretary Calls on Kosovars to Stop Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 23 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook called on Wednesday all Kosovo residents to restrain from
violence and to live together in peace.
</P>
<P>
He promised that the NATO-led peacekeeping forces would protect
the safety of the  Kosovo people of all
nationalities.
</P>
<P>
Cook, together with foreign ministers from Italy, France and
Germany, toured Kosovo  on Wednesday, the first visit
to Kosovo by high-ranking Western officials since the NATO-led
peacekeeping mission began on June 12.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held on Wednesday night, Cook called on
Kosovars to halt violence so that all people can live in peace in
the war-torn Serb province.
</P>
<P>
He also asked Kosovo Serbs and Montenegrins not to leave the
troubled region. All ethnic Albanians he met with in Kosovo wished
Serbs to stay, he said.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the four foreign ministers met separately with
NATO's Kosovo Commander Michael Jackson and head of the UN.
mission in Kosovo, Sergio Vieira de Mello.
</P>
