<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Consumers Concerned about Safety of Imported Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese consumers are concerned
about food safety in the wake of the contamination incident in
Europe and have been cautioned against eating meat, poultry and
dairy products from Belgium, France, Germany and Netherlands,
today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yuanchao, secretary general of the China Consumers
Association, gave the advice at a news conference in Beijing on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He also advised consumers to eat domestic products which have
proven to be free from dioxin contamination instead of buying
products with ingredients from unnamed suppliers.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, China banned the imports and suspended sales
of products produced after January 15 from the four countries, as
the cancer-causing dioxin stirred a widespread health scare in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, the Ministry of Health may lift the ban on sales of
the products from the four countries if they can provide valid
papers verifying safety of their products.
</P>
<P>
The documents include: test reports on the products' dioxin
content issued by authoritative testing centers and approved by
health departments in their home countries, and papers issued by
their home countries and the European Union permitting the sale of
the products after June 1, according to a circular issued by the
ministry's Law and Supervision Department on Tuesday.
</P>
