<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Navy Searches for Missing Malaysia Ship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Navy is searching
for a Malaysia-owned ship, earlier believed to have been sunk off
Sri Lanka's eastern coast last month, but now suspected to have
been captured by the country's Tamil rebels.
</P>
<P>
The International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) has been
asked by the Singapore-based International Maritime Bureau to
contact the rebels and make inquiries about the ship, informed
sources here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Navy officials were quoted as saying they had not found the
ship which had been reported sunk and had no idea what had
happened to the vessel.
</P>
<P>
The freighter Sik Yang with a crew of 15, had been carrying
4,000 tons of salt when it disappeared without trace. It had been
en route to the port of Malacca in Malaysia from India on May 25,
the day it was reported missing.
</P>
<P>
There are suspicions that the vessel which disappeared on calm
seas was hijacked by the Tamil rebels who have been fighting a war
 for a separate Tamil state in Sri Lanka since 1983.
</P>
<P>
If the ship had been sunk there would have been some evidence
such as an oil slick, debris, or a washed-up body, but none of
these had been found either by the navy or fishermen in the area,
the navy officials added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
