<HEADLINE> FM: Panama Able to Protect Canal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Panamanian Foreign Minister
Jorge Eduardo Ritter Wednesday rejected a U.S. commander's
comments and reaffirmed categorically that his country is capable
of protecting the canal.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in reply to U.S. South Command Chief
Charles Wilhelm, who questioned Panama's capability to protect the
canal.
</P>
<P>
Wilhelm, testifying before the Senate Foreign Relations
subcommittee on the Western Hemisphere Tuesday, said Panama does
not have the capacity to defend the canal from Colombian guerrilla
raids, and announced that the U.S. will act unilaterally if the
security of the canal is threatened.
</P>
<P>
Ritter said the U.S. commander's comments are groundless and
totally untrue, noting that his country has now assumed control of
the canal and that Panamanian police are patrolling the
installations.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said the U.S. military presence in Panama
has historically been linked to the application of the U.S.
military political strategy in the region, and that it never had
anything to do with the security of the country.
</P>
<P>
"The aim of the U.S. military bases on Panamanian territory has
never been to protect the inter-oceanic canal, and much less the
protection of the borders," he added.
</P>
<P>
Under the Torrijos-Carter treaties, the United States must
withdraw all its military forces from Panama by the end of the
year, a process that is well under way.
</P>
<P>
Ritter said it is improper for the U.S. to use these false
accusations as an excuse to give the impression that the canal is
under threat.
</P>
<P>
"The canal is at present functioning normally and at the moment
is in fact extending its capacity in order to serve the needs of
international maritime commerce," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
