<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adapting Price Controls And Services To Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 25 (Xinhua) -- China's government price control
departments and service institutions are being asked to use more
legal means to regulate market prices, in a move to protect
economic growth and the rights and interests of businesses.
</P>
<P>
Twenty years of price reforms have made it possible for China
to leave the prices of an overwhelming majority of commodities and
services to the swing of the market. And price regulation and
consultation have become major forms in which government
departments provide services to society.
</P>
<P>
Wang Chunzheng, vice-minister of the State Development
Planning Commission, told a national meeting on price controls
recently that the government is responsible for both regulating
macro-economic activity and pricing a certain limited number of
commodities and services over which it still has direct control.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to retain price regulation at the early
stage of a socialist market economy. "Governments have to decide
whether or not a price set by an enterprise is legitimate," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He explained that government departments should better manage
price controls and help handle problems that businesses themselves
can't solve, but should leave those they can solve to themselves
or to price service firms.
</P>
<P>
Pricing services are necessary for building a socialist legal
system, Wang said. Last year, price control offices appraised 39
billion yuan worth of goods, 34 billion yuan of which had some
form of criminal activity involved in their pricing.
</P>
<P>
The senior official also urged local areas to standardize price
controls to safeguard fair and open market competition.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 2,800 pricing affairs offices, employing
more than 15,000 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
