<HEADLINE> Glacier At Source Of Yangtze River Getting Smaller </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- A glacier at the source of China's
Yangtze River has shrunk 600 meters over the past 30 years,
according to a recent study.
</P>
<P>
The study was done by a team headed by Xi Qingji, the director
of Qinghai Mapping Institute No.1 at a place 5,367 meters above
sea level on Geladandong Snowy Peak in May.
</P>
<P>
Xi's study has been recognized by the Chinese Academy of
Sciences' Lanzhou Research Institute of Glaciology and
Cryopedology.
</P>
<P>
He made the conclusion by comparing recent surveys with aerial
photographs taken in 1970, Xi explains, and a great number of
Chinese scientists have been amazed at the rapid shrinkage.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze comes from Tanggula Mountains, which have thirty-
three 6,000-m. snow-covered peaks, of which Geladandong is the
tallest. The mountains also have 59 glaciers. A survey done in
1976 showed a glacier that covered a 750-square-kilometer area at
that time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
