<HEADLINE> EU, U.S. Promise to Help Ukraine Close Down Chernobyl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The European Union and the United
States have reaffirmed  they will provide sufficient
economic aid to help Ukraine close down the Chernobyl nuclear
power station by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement issued on Wednesday, the EU and the U.S.
expressed the hope that Kiev will shut down the troubled station
by the end of 2000, and promised full financial support to
alleviate the burden arising from the close-down of the nuclear
power plant and from Ukraine's efforts to develop its energy
industry.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian government has repeatedly complained that if the
Western countries do not implement the agreement reached five
years ago, Ukraine will not have the ability to close down
Chernobyl as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement reached between Ukraine and the G7
countries in 1995, Ukraine has the obligation to shut down
Chernobyl nuclear power station before 2000. Meanwhile the Western
countries should provide economic assistance to help Ukraine build
two other nuclear power stations. However, the pledged two billion
U.S. dollar foreign aid has not yet arrived by now.
</P>
<P>
One of the reactors of the Chernobyl power plant exploded on
April 26, 1986, causing a serious nuclear disaster in Ukraine.
</P>
</TEXT>
