<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Sees Falling Consumer Price Index </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's consumer price index in
June was down 0.3 percent from May, Vietnam News Agency Thursday
quoted Vietnam's General Department of Statistics as saying.
</P>
<P>
It is the fourth monthly decline recorded so far this year.
</P>
<P>
The price for food continued dropping in June by 2.9 percent
from May or equivalent to 95.1 percent of that for December last
year.
</P>
<P>
Localities seeing decreases in food prices included Hanoi (3.1
percent), Hai Phong (5.5 percent), Thua Thien-Hue Province (5.6
percent) and Da Nang City (3.5 percent). However, An Giang and Can
Tho provinces saw increases of 3.4 percent and 0.2 percent,
respectively, in food prices due to exports.
</P>
<P>
The decline of the food prices was attributed to this year's
bumper winter-spring harvest with an estimated output of 13.9
million tons of rice, the highest so far.
</P>
<P>
Drops of between 0.2 and 0.3 percent were also recorded in the
prices of soft drinks, tobacco, traveling and post services and
others.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, increases ranging from 0.2-1 percent were recorded
with the prices of schooling facilities up 1 percent, household
goods and utensils 0.4 percent and pharmaceutical products 0.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
The price of the U.S. dollar was unchanged in June while the
price of gold fell 2.4 percent from May.
</P>
<P>
With decreases of prices in the four consecutive months, the
price index in the first half of this year increased by only 1.6
percent compared with that of December last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
