<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Canberra Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The High Court of Australia dealt One Nation Party a blow
Wednesday by disqualifying its only successful candidate in last
year's federal election.
</P>
<P>
-- A second front-bench member of the Australian government and
parliamentary secretary to Prime Minister John Howard, Bill
Heffernan, admitted Wednesday night that he had breached,
inadvertently, the ministerial code of conduct.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review:
</P>
<P>
-- The Australian government is poised to deregulate the
gasoline industry, allowing the four major oil companies to
rationalize their service station networks in return for lower
gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
The Age:
</P>
<P>
-- Samantha McDonald, a 31-year-old policewoman who was
dismissed from Australia's Victoria state police force after being
injured during training, was awarded 300,000 Australian dollars
(198,000 U.S. dollars) on Wednesday. She had told the court that
she had suffered excruciating pain after a male recruit wrenched
her arm. 
</P>
