<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Senate Endorses Ministerial Nominees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Senate approved Wednesday
42 of the 49 ministerial nominees proposed by President Olusegun
Obasanjo, concluding the marathon clearance only days before its
expiration.
</P>
<P>
The list to be announced by the president will form Nigeria's
first civilian government in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
Seven candidates were deleted from the list, which was not yet
published, because the states of their origin have already secured
enough representation in the government, according to Senate
sources.
</P>
<P>
"We will communicate our final decision to the president, who
will thereafter make it public along with the portfolios," said
Senator Joseph Waku after the ending of Wednesday's session of the
upper house of Nigeria's National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The clearance of the list was delayed when the senators were
asking for more personal information on the nominees last week.
</P>
<P>
The clearance was also proceeded amid severe quarrels between
the majority People's Democratic Party (PDP) and the two minority
parties, the Alliance for Democracy (AD) and All People's Party (
APP)
</P>
<P>
The AD and APP senators walked out of the National Assembly
Building Tuesday to protest a corruption accusation against them,
leaving the PDP senators continuing their debate alone in the
building.
</P>
<P>
The protest took place when an AD-sponsored motion seeking to
censure PDP Senator Gbenga Aluko was dropped in the Senate. The
motion demanded an apology from Aluko for his allegation in a
newspaper pronouncement, accusing some AD and APP senators of
involving in bribery and corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
