<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden to Dispatch Peacekeepers to Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The Swedish government decided
on Wednesday to send a battalion of 800 peacekeepers and 63
civilian personnel to join the international peace-keeping forces
in the Yugoslav province of Kosovo (KFOR).
</P>
<P>
The Swedish peace-keeping force, including specialized
engineers, is expected to complete its preparations for deployment
by November, the foreign and defense ministries said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"Through stabilization in Kosovo, security is increased in the
entire region," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of the 800 peacekeepers in Kosovo and those
already in Bosnia and Herzegovina will cost about 900 million
crowns (about 110 million U.S. dollars) annually, which will be
covered by the budget of the Swedish Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The government has also decided to earmark 84 million crowns (
about 10 million dollars) during 1999-2000 for the participation
in civil forces called the United Nations Mission in Kosovo (UNMIK)
. These will include 50 civil police officers, four liaison
officers and nine legal medical experts.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish government has also decided to increase
humanitarian aid to Kosovo to help the region's reconstruction
efforts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
