<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rising Sea Levels Could Have Impact On Southern China's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 24 (Xinhua) -- A study has found that the sea
around Guangdong, Hong Kong, and Macao will rise by 10 cm to 30 cm
in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
Water in the Pearl River estuary is expected to rise 30 cm and
on the western side of the Leizhou Peninsula to rise 10 cm. This
will take place from 1990 to 2030 and will have a significant
impact in many areas like the coastal economy, land resources, and
the environment, members of the study team say.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academy of Sciences' Guangzhou Branch and the
Guangdong Provincial Institute of Sciences started four years ago
with more than 100 scientists and technicians participating on the
"Impact and counter measures of rising sea levels on coastal
economic development of Guangdong Province" study.
</P>
<P>
They call for better standards in water control projects and
works on the coast and suggested building a major water control
project on the Pearl River Delta to control the volume of water
from the Xijiang and Beijiang rivers, two tributaries of the Pearl,
and to alleviate possible disasters from a rising sea level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shandong Boosts Its Private Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province now
leads the country in private business operations boasting 105,000
such enterprises, employing 1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
There are also 2.79 million self-employed households with 6.21
million employees.
</P>
<P>
These private businesses have a combined registered capital of
62.8 billion yuan (7.56 billion US dollars), accounting for 9.3
percent of the total in the province, up 1.6 percentage points on
a yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Renjing, director of the Provincial Administration for
Industry and Commerce, attributed the local booming private
economy to the national policy of upgrading non-state businesses
as an important component of the country's economy, instead of
being merely complementary as before, an encouragement which was
decreed at the 15th National Party Congress in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Shandong authorities have now sworn to step up support for
private enterprises and self-employed households and to a create
more favorable business environment for them.
</P>
<P>
The second largest province after Henan in China in terms of
population, Shandong now also ranks third nationwide in terms of
GDP.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
