<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Township Businesses Boost Export in Hubei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Export losses made by foreign-funded
enterprises in central China's Hubei Province this year may be
written off by a booming foreign trade conducted by township
businesses, according to the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
The township sector, which only took off in 1993, has just
become a driving force to revive the province's waning exports,
said Deputy Governor Zhang Hongxiang.
</P>
<P>
The sector exported goods worth over two billion yuan in the
first four months of this year, up 10 percent compared to the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
There were more than 600 township firms having foreign trade
licenses in Hubei by the end of last year. They realized a
combined 8.3 billion yuan-worth of exports in 1998, compared with
eight million yuan 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Tianyu Garment Firm, for example, has successfully entered
overseas markets in North America, Europe and Africa. Its exports
reached 23 million U.S. dollars-worth last year.
</P>
<P>
High value-added exports, such as chemicals, light industrial
products, foodstuffs and medicines, account for 40 percent of the
total, up 20 percent from five years ago.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to bestow more flexible policies to help
township enterprises get involved in foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
