<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rican-Nicaraguan Dispute Re-emerges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The dispute between Costa Rica
and Nicaragua over navigation rights on the San Juan River has
risen once again as presidents of both countries issued statements
Wednesday to defend each other's stand.
</P>
<P>
Nicaraguan President Arnoldo Aleman rejected on Wednesday once
again Costa Rica's request to transport armed civil guards on the
river, the Costa Rican press reported. The dispute led to a crisis
in bilateral relations last year.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican President Miguel Angel Rodriguez, in return,
reaffirmed his stance on Wednesday that their rights must be
respected.
</P>
<P>
He said he would consider President Aleman's request last week
to extend an migratory amnesty granted to Nicaraguan citizens, due
to expire on July 31, but added that there were growing pressures
against such an extension.
</P>
<P>
Local press quoted certain treaties as saying that Costa Rica
has the right of free passage on the river. However, Nicaragua
exercises sovereign rights over the river.
</P>
<P>
In his statement, President Aleman quoted an old phrase, "
Sovereignty is not discussed, it is defended with arms," referring
to the case.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that around 150,000 Nicaraguans have taken
advantage of the amnesty to enter Costa Rica. However, Councilor
Roberto Rojas said that there might be up to 600,000 Nicaraguans
living in Costa Rica illegally.
</P>
<P>
The massive influx of Nicaraguans into Costa Rica was
attributed to the difficult economic situation and a high
unemployment rate in Nicaragua. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Explore LNG Market in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia is to explore
possibilities of selling liquefied natural gas (LNG) from its
Tangguh field in Irian Jaya to China, Antara News Agency Thursday
quoted a spokesman for state-owned oil and natural gas company
Pertamina as saying.
</P>
<P>
Pertamina's President Director Martiono Hadianto said he had
met President B.J. Habibie on Wednesday to report that he would
soon visit China to sound out relevant authorities, business or
industrial circles there about the possibility of marketing
Indonesian LNG in the world's most populous country.
</P>
<P>
The Tangguh gas field in Indonesia's easternmost province of
Irian Jaya was known to hold up to 14.6 trillion cubic feet of
natural gas reserves.
</P>
<P>
The field was being developed by contractor-operator Arthur
Richfield Company (Arco) of the United States and LNG production
facilities were also being set up in the region.
</P>
<P>
Asked about LNG consumption in China, Hadianto said so far
China was mostly using oil and coal but lately demand for clean
energy was rising so rapidly that China was considering to use
natural gas.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that Indonesian LNG exports had recently been
through a difficult period due to a decline in world demand and
the emergence of more competitors in the international market.
</P>
<P>
Regular takers of Indonesian LNG so far are South Korea, Japan
and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Hadianto said Pertamina needed to sound out sales possibilities
abroad properly as LNG production costs were very high.
</P>
<P>
"So even before the LNG production facilities are in place, we
need to know who is going to buy the product," Hadianto added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
