<HEADLINE> Preparations for Latin America-EU Summit Nearly Ready </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Officials from Latin
America, the Caribbean and the European Union are putting final
touches on draft documents for a summit scheduled for early next
week in Rio de Janeiro, summit coordinators said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two main documents -- the Declaration of Rio de Janeiro and
an annex detailing "Priorities for Joint Action" -- will be fine-
tuned on Friday and Saturday before going to the meeting of
foreign ministers for approval on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Both drafts will be discussed by the heads of state and
government from the 48 participating countries at the summit next
Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
General Coordinator of the summit, Brazilian Foreign Ministry
official Luiz Augusto de Castro Neves said at a press conference
at the Modern Art Museum here that Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso will preside over the opening and closing
sessions of the summit.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder will preside over
discussions on economic and trade issues. On the issue of
international finance, Chilean President Eduardo Frei and Cuban
President Fidel Castro will represent the Latin American and
Caribbean countries respectively while French President Jacques
Chirac will speak on behalf of the Europeans.
</P>
<P>
Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo will chair discussions on
issues of culture, education and humanism, the coordinator said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the two documents manifest the political
willingness to intensify relations in the fields of politics,
economics, trade, culture and humanism between the Latin American
countries and the EU in general, and between the Southern Common
Market (Mercosur) and the EU in particular.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, a major trading bloc in the western hemisphere,
comprises Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay and Paraguay with Chile and
Bolivia as its associate members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
