<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans To Use WB Loans to Increase Water Flow on Li River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China plans to use World Bank loans
to speed up water flow on the Li River in the city of Guilin, a
tourism spot known for its picturesque landscape in China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the river during dry seasons flows
at only 10 cu.m. per second and stops navigation because of
insufficient water level. Analysts say that 30 cu.m. per second is
needed and that this is especially necessary when tourists visit
the city.
</P>
<P>
The water supply work will consist of a new reservoir, at least
two water diversion projects, and a couple of other projects that
will be financed through different channels, one of which is World
Bank loans.
</P>
<P>
Construction will start this year and will be finished in two
or three years. When it is finished, water flow will reach 40 cu.m.
per second during dry season, and boating on the river will be a
year-round event, experts say.
</P>
<P>
The city is also increasing efforts to stop industrial
pollution and 98 percent of the city's industrial waste water is
being treated and 72 percent of treated waste water have reached
various required standards.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
