<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Myanmar Takes Measures to Eradicate Drugs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 24 (Xinhua) -- In the 1820s, the British invaded
Myanmar, putting the country under its colonial rule and to
effectively enslave the Myanmar people, the British colonialists
introduced poppy cultivation and narcotics into the country in
1846.
</P>
<P>
Since then, narcotic drugs have run rampant in Myanmar and have
been illicitly sold to every part of the world.
</P>
<P>
The "Golden Triangle" area, which borders on Thailand and Laos,
is known as the world's largest place of origin where opium is
produced.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest Myanmar official statistics, the total
poppy cultivation area in the country is 61,236 hectares with an
annual opium production of 665.28 tons which could be refined into
66.52 tons of heroin.
</P>
<P>
After Myanmar regained independence from British colonial rule
on January 4, 1948, successive governments have taken various
measures in an effort to eliminate drugs.
</P>
<P>
One of the main measures taken was promulgation of
anti-narcotics laws, trying to put drug abuse in the country under
control and be governed by laws.
</P>
<P>
The country enacted the first Narcotics and Dangerous Drugs Law
in 1974, to which it made amendments and supplements in 1983 and
1988.
</P>
<P>
Later on January 27, 1993, Myanmar promulgated the second
Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances Law, abolishing and
replacing the 1974 anti-drug law. The only difference is that the
1993 law allows for death penalty to be imposed upon drug
violators under certain circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Setting up special drug control organizations is the next
measure Myanmar has taken. To strengthen the leadership and
supervision in the drug control work, Myanmar formed the Central
Committee for Drug Abuse Control in 1975.
</P>
<P>
Increase of government's investment in the development of
border areas and ethnic races, raising of the living standard of
inhabitants in these areas, changing of their traditional
livelihood which depends on poppy cultivation and cutting off the
drug sources are also measures taken by Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
According to official data, during the past 10 years between
1988 and 1998, the Myanmar government injected 14.6 billion kyats
(48.6 million U.S. dollars) for the development of border areas
and ethnic races, building 15,565 kilometers of roads, 714
bridges, 43 hospitals, 79 clinics, 44 rural health centers, 411
schools, 18 dams, 18 livestock breeding farms, eight power
stations, 77 TV relay stations and 52 posts and telecommunications
offices.
</P>
<P>
The building of these facilities greatly improved the
conditions of transport, health and education in the border areas,
promoting the economic development there.
</P>
<P>
The most important is that some farmers have cultivated
sugarcane and buckwheat, substituting poppy. In 1998, the
cultivation area of poppy substitute crops stood at 5,898 hectares
and it increased to 4,916 hectares in 1999. Due to the expanded
cultivation area of these substitute crops, the production of drug
and its supply dropped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
