<HEADLINE> European Bourses Dip on U.S Rate Fears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON June 23 (Xinhua) - European stock markets fell sharply
Wednesday amid rekindled fears of a hike in US interest rates
later this month.
</P>
<P>
The leading UK FTSE 100 finished weaker on fears of interest
rates hikes in the United States. Merger news in Britain failed to
boost sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The blue chips ended down 55.9 points, or 0.85 percent, at
6496.5 after an agreement by Lloyds TSB to pay 11 billion US
dollars for mutual group Scottish Widows met with a lukewarm
reception.
</P>
<P>
Lloyds stock rose at first but then fell back, finishing the
day at 899.5p, a drop of 2.7 percent as analysts concluded that
Lloyds may have paid too much.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the electronically traded Xetra Dax extended
earlier losses to close 1.3 percent lower at 5399.11, a loss of
just under 70 points.
</P>
<P>
Automakers BWM and VW led the market down after BMW revealed an
unexpectedly large rescue package for Rover. Fears that VW was
going to buy Scania, the Swedish truck maker, also depressed
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
Paris stocks also drifted lower after interest rates worries
depressed Wall Street. The Cac 40 index was down more than 1
percent at 4481, well below its record highs of last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
