<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Decides to Postpone East Timor Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 23 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Wednesday decided to postpone for two weeks a August 8
vote on the future of East Timor because of security concerns and
logistical problems.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the United Nations Security Council, Annan did
not give a precise date.
</P>
<P>
In the report, Annan said pro-integration militias were
intimidating voters in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
"Militia activities continue to have a constricting effect on
political freedom, silencing pro-independence activists and their
supporters and forcing them into hiding, thus jeopardising the
necessary openness of the consultation process," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he hoped registration of voters would begin on July
13, a delay of three weeks, which would give U.N. staff time to be
deployed in all areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the the security situation will have improved
sufficiently by then to enable me to make a position determination
of the security conditions so that the operational phases of the
consultation can begin," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said in the meantime, Indonesia and Portugal had
agreed to a two-week postponement of the ballot date.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is fielding a mission of 900, including 270
civilian police, 50 military officers and hundreds of electoral
officials and administrators.
</P>
<P>
Annan said delays in obtaining Indonesia visas and slow action
by the Security Council have slowed the deployment of the U.N.
mission in East Timor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
