<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premier League Windfall Tax Call </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The Premier League has rejected
calls for England's richest football clubs to pay a windfall tax
to help the grassroots game, according to a BBC report.
</P>
<P>
The Institute for Public Policy Research (IPPR) is calling for
a redistribution of money from television rights to improve grass
roots football.
</P>
<P>
In a report on the future of sport in the UK, it acknowledges
the government's Football Task Force's proposal for a 5% levy on
the money raised from the next television rights deal.
</P>
<P>
The current contract between BSkyB, the BBC and the Premier
League is worth 185m a year to the clubs.
</P>
<P>
If there was to be a 5% levy on that total, a windfall of 9.25m
each year would go to the grassroots.
</P>
<P>
This money would be used to improve facilities for football at
schools and community sports fields, helping to create the stars
of the future.
</P>
<P>
But a spokesman for the Premier League said that its clubs -
the 20 top teams in England - already did their bit.
</P>
<P>
The Premier League estimates that 50m was paid into Government
coffers by clubs in the form of taxes and other levies such as
National Insurance during the past season.
</P>
<P>
It also said that clubs in the English game's top division had
spent 50m over the past four years in the game outside the Premier
League.
</P>
<P>
This was through a variety of means, including the Football
League, Football Trust and new academies for young football
players.
</P>
<P>
"This windfall tax proposal seems to have been rather plucked
out of the air without any real regard for the way much is already
being invested in the game," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"Premier League clubs who face enormous and growing cost
pressures already make a significant contribution to the game and
to their local communities.
</P>
<P>
"Threats of a windfall tax will do nothing to aid that process
and could undermine the commercial well being of our top clubs who
have increasingly to compete in a truly international market place.
"
</P>
<P>
The idea of a windfall tax has been used in the past in the UK,
most recently in 1997 when former state owned companies had to pay
a one off tax.
</P>
<P>
The think-tank also stressed the connection between sport and
other areas of social policy, including health and social
exclusion.
</P>
<P>
One of its other suggestions is for doctors to be able to
prescribe sport.
</P>
<P>
Among other proposals will be a reduction in the number of
sports supported by the Sports Councils.
</P>
<P>
The sports should be selected according to international
standing or visibility, emotional importance to the country - and
cost-effectiveness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
