<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Speeds Up Expressway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, a remote border area in northwest China, has used a loan
from the World Bank of 450 million U.S. dollars to build
expressways.
</P>
<P>
The loans make up one tenth of the total sum provided by the
World Bank for highway construction in China, a regional
government official said.
</P>
<P>
Work on the first road started in March in 1995, at a cost of
three billion yuan, of which 150 million U.S. dollars came from
the World Bank. The 283-km-road between Turpan and Dahuangshan
opened to traffic in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
Work on the second one, which links Urumqi with Kuitun, a
distance of 266 km, started in April, 1997. It will cost an
estimated five billion yuan. The World Bank is to provide 300
million U.S. dollars for the project. The road is expected to be
completed in September 2000.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the region is making preparations for the
construction of third highway, which will link Kuitun City with
Sailimu Lake, a distance of 323 km, with World Bank loans.
</P>
<P>
A feasibility study for a fourth highway, with a designed
length of 464 km, is now under way.
</P>
<P>
Construction of new expressways will accelerate economic growth
in Xinjiang, where highway transport accounts for 95 percent of
the total volume of goods transported.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0343 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exiled Iraqi Opposition Asks U.S. to Take "Bold Action" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The exiled Iraqi opposition
asked the United States on Wednesday for "bold action" to help
them overthrow President Saddam Hussein, but the Clinton
administration deemed the time was not ripe for that kind of
action.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Chalabi, a member of the executive presidency of the
Iraqi National Congress (INC), told a Senate committee that the
opposition wanted more protection given by the U.S. military, to
embolden internal opponents fighting the Iraqi government.
</P>
<P>
"What we need is bold action," he said, arguing that the
opponents inside Iraq were looking to get equipment and training
through the INC under the Iraq Liberation Act.
</P>
<P>
The Iraq Liberation Act, passed by U.S. Congress last year,
gave the administration power to give the Iraqi opposition goods
and services worth up to $98 million, mostly in the form of
surplus equipment from the Department of Defense.
</P>
<P>
So far the Clinton administration has not used the power and
is planning to release mainly office and communications equipment.
</P>
<P>
Beth Jones, the principal deputy assistant secretary of state
for Near Eastern Affairs, told the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee that the administration did not see "an effective use
of military equipment now."
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton decided last year to add "regime
change" to U.S. policy toward Iraq and began to reactivate the
INC. But his administration said it was premature to give
military support for the INC.
</P>
<P>
"There are a host of issues that must be resolved before we
can hae confidence that providing arms would advance our
objectives of promoting a change of regime," Jones said.
</P>
<P>
The United States, in its attempt to topple the Iraqi
government, will help convene a meeting next month in a Western
capital, which is meant to bring together all opposition groups
and united them under a single umbrella organization, possibly
using the INC label. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0344 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
