<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0345 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Billion U.S. Dollars Needed to Save Mediterranean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 23 (Xinhua) -- A grand total of 10 billion U.S.
dollars will be needed to save the Mediterranean from death by
pollution, an international conference estimated Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The international conference, which held in Italian south city
of Reggio Calabria, said the money is needed to clean up urban and
industrial wastes, for toxic waste management, monitoring of
water-courses for pollution, public information and education
programs, and national action plans.
</P>
<P>
The Mediterranean is a closed sea whose only major outlet
permitting an exchange of its water with one of the world's oceans
is to the Atlantic through the straits of Gibraltar.
</P>
<P>
The conference also accepted a proposal from environmentalist
groups on hand at the meeting to set up a register plotting the
loading, unloading and movements of the main agents of pollution
in the Mediterranean area.
</P>
<P>
About 20 percent of the world's crude oil is transported
through the Mediterranean, and countries with intensive
agriculture such as Italy's use large amounts of fertilizers and
pesticides.
</P>
<P>
According to recent figures, Italy, for example, spreads two
million tons of phosphates and nitrates on its fields each year,
and much of this eventually finishes in the sea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990624.0346 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Says Fund for Kosovo Mission Is Empty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations said
Wednesday that a fund set up for its civilian operations in
Kosovo, a Serbian province, was empty, making it impossible to pay
for local civilian servants and small-scale infrastructure
projects.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Interim Administration in Kosovo (UNMIK) is attempting
to set up seven commissions among Kosovo Albanians and Serbs on
such issues as health, education, public utilities, justice, trade
and agriculture, finance and communications, U.N. spokesman Fred
Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of funding to execute UNMIK's work is a top
concern," he told a press conference, "Trust funds have been set
up but so far remain empty."
</P>
<P>
"Money is urgently needed to pay for the civilian servants --
many of whom have not been paid for more than two months," the
spokesman said. "Another priority for funding so-called 'Quick
Impact Project' which are small-scaled projects ranging from
repairing damaged water supplies, mosques and churches."
</P>
<P>
UNMIK, he said, also needs money to procure computers for the
judges to carry out their work.
</P>
<P>
Under a peace plan, adopted by the U.N. Security Council on
June 10, the United Nations is to administrate the civilian
component in parallel with the peacekeepers who are flying U.N.
flag in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The European Union, which is responsible for the post-war
reconstruction, estimates that rebuilding Kosovo would cost about
1 billion euros, the equivalent of 1.03 billion U.S. dollars, per
year for next three years with half the funds coming from 15
European countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. mission will have the task of resettling and proving
an interim administration for up to a million ethnic Albanian
refugees, many of whom sought refuge in neighboring countries
after NATO's March 24 bombing of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
UNMIK is also expected to provide international police advise.
However, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has to appoint an
overall administrative, called his special representative, which
he has not made yet a final decision, naming instead Sergio Vieira
de Mello, U.N. under-secretary-general for humanitarian affairs,
on an interim basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
