<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Chinese Sport Works Shown in Olympic Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Some 150 pieces of works about
sports in ancient China are on show at the Olympic Museum in
Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
He Zhenliang, Chairman of the Cultural Commission of the
International Olympic Committee (IOC), formally opened the
exhibition "5000 Years of Sport in China - Art and Tradition" here
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"With its origins in the Yellow River Valley, the Chinese
civilization has its own time-honored sports like all other
ancient civilizations," He said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 5,000 years, he told more than 100 guests at the
opening ceremony, the Chinese people have created a great variety
of sports and games.
</P>
<P>
"A number of modern sports can be traced back to ancient China:
weightlifting, swimming, archery and equestrian sports in summer,
and skating and skiing in winter," he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the visitors to the exhibition would
gain a better knowledge and understanding of China.
</P>
<P>
In a written message to mark the exhibition, IOC President Juan
Antonio Samaranch praised the Chinese Olympic Committee and the
Chinese athletes for their contributions to the Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
Hosting the exhibition entitled "5000 Years of Sport in China,"
Samaranch said "the Olympic Museum in Lausanne will enable its
many visitors to discover a remarkable exhibition presenting a
highly original vision of sport".
</P>
<P>
The exhibits have been provided by China Sport's Museum in
Beijing and the Musee Nationale des Arts Asiatiques-Guimet in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
Having attracted thousands of visitors since it was open to the
public on June 17, the exhibition will conclude on October 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
