<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Seeds Advance in Wimbledon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- All women's seeded players playing
on Wednesday advanced into the third round of the singles event at
the Wimbledon tennis championships.
</P>
<P>
Out of the eight women's seeds on display, only second seed
Steffi Graf of Germany was taken the distance as the others had
relatively easy straight sets victories.
</P>
<P>
Graf, seven-time Wimbledon champion, survived a scare as she
faced an inspired Marian De Swardt of South Africa who served and
volleyed exceptionally to take the opening set 6-4.
</P>
<P>
However, Graf brought herself back into the match with some
trademark forehand winners, while De Swardt was unable to maintain
the high standard of the first set. Graf went on to win the next
two sets at 6-3, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
The German, who is now the highest seed left in the competition
after the shock defeat of Martina Hingis of Switzerland yesterday,
will now meet Corina Morariu who took Graf to three sets at last
year's U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
Graf's long-time rival Monica Seles of the United States
enjoyed an extremely easy victory in comparison. Seles, the No. 4
seed this year, whitewashed Germany's Marlene Weingartner 6-0, 6-0,
hitting an astonishing 92% returns in court. Seles simply ran the
German opponent ragged and Weingartner, whose appearance this year
is her first ever at Wimbledon, had no response.
</P>
<P>
Seles will face talented 17-year-old Croatian Mirjana Lucic in
the next round.
</P>
<P>
Joining Seles in the third round is fellow American Venus
Williams, who defeated a stubborn Elena Tatarkova 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the spotlight focused on the 18-year-old
Russian Anna Kournikova, as she won a tough encounter against
Maria Vento of Venezuela 7-5, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Other seeds who also played early were Amanda Coetzer, the No.
12 seed, who defeated Japan's Miho Saeki 6-4, 6-1, and Sandrine
Testud, who won a prospectively tough match with Barbara Rittner
quite easily, 7-6 (7-2), 6-1. Testud's French compatriot eighth
seeded Nathalie Tauziat, who reached the final last year, beat
Amanda Hopmans of the Netherlands 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
In men's section, Jim Courier of the United States shoved 12th
seed Carlos Moya out of the Wimbledon championships in the second
round in a five-set tussle of former French Open champions.
</P>
<P>
But five-times champion Pete Sampras needed just 81 minutes to
crush Canada's Sebastien Laureau 6-4, 6-2, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Laureau showed the odd flash of inspiration -- even breaking
Sampras's serve twice -- but didn't have the weaponry to hurt the
top seed who is yet to lose a set and gave a masterclass in
consistency.
</P>
<P>
Courier showed once more what a determined streetfighter he is
in toppling former world number one Moya 6-3, 3-6, 7-6, 3-6, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old American, who was himself world number one back
in 1992, proved that his power has not lost its edge against Moya'
s claycourt skills.
</P>
<P>
Spanish 16th seed Felix Mantilla became the first men's seed to
fall at this year's Wimbledon, losing 6-2, 6-4, 6-7, 6-2 to
American Paul Goldstein minutes before Moya went under.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in 12 years, Wimbledon had seen all 16 men's
seeds survive into the second round.
</P>
<P>
Men's ninth seed Greg Rusedski thrashed British compatriot
Arvind Parmar, a qualifier, 6-3, 6-4, 7-6. The 21-year-old Parmar
took just 11 points on Rusedski's serve.
</P>
<P>
Rusedski now faces an interesting test against Swede Magnus
Norman, who beat Goran Ivanisevic 14-12 in the fifth set in an
epic second-round match at Wimbledon two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Norman, who has a long-standing heart problem which doctors
have warned could curtail his professional career, beat Fabrice
Santoro of France 6-2, 6-3, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
Thirteenth seed Karol Kucera of Slovakia made it into the third
round with a 7-6, 6-3, 6-2 victory over Brazilian qualifier Andre
Sa while 1997 runner-up Cedric Pioline also went through after
beating fellow Frenchman Arnaud Clement 6-3, 6-1, 6-3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
