<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Falls For Third Straight Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial average
fell for a third straight session Wednesday as investors worried
about the Federal Reserve's next move on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow closed down 54.77 at 10,666.86. The index lost 133.93
points in the two previous sessions.
</P>
<P>
Persistent rise in the bond yields made investors uncertain
whether the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates more than
once. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond rose to 6.11 percent
today from 6.06 percent Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Investors got eased about higher interest rates last week as
they believed that the Federal Reserve would raise interest rates
but the action would not be too drastic. But now some feared that
the Federal Reserve would raise interest rates two or even three
times.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mixed. The technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 17.86 at 2,598.12 and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 2.82 at 1,333.06. The Nasdaq was pushed
higher by a number of Internet players who posted modest gains.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 2.36 at 630.75 and the American
Stock Exchange composite index rose 5.69 at 771.16. The Russell
2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.29 at 447.04.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,760 down, 1,257 up and 555
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 720.42 million shares from 710.31
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
